title: Frame agreement with NGO (Siemenpuu)
description:
The project involves organizing an international conference on ecological democracy and community rights for 200 participants in Sri Lanka. Local communities in the global South lack decision-making power over the natural resources surrounding them. As a r
esult, many communities have become marginalized victims of modern development and environmental damage caused by it. Ecological democracy provides a framework that would enable community participation in decision-making over local environment in their own
 terms, instead of those of companies or officials. In order to make  informed decisions and act accordingly, the communities and grassroots organizations need better access to environmental information. The two-day conference will be held in the turn of S
eptember-October 2014 in Kandy, Sri Lanka. The conference precedes a general meeting of Friends of the Earth International (FoEI), which will be held in the same place. Half of the participants in the conference will be local activists and community repres
entatives, and the other half FoEI network members from 76 countries. The implementing organization, Centre for Environmental Justice, is FoEI 's member organization in Sri Lanka. The conference enables exchanging information and experiences  on environmen
tal problems and democratic management of enviroment between local actors and those coming from different parts of the world. A declaration and action plan to achieve ecological democracy will be made in the conference, and afterwards a publication on the 
conference presentations and discussions will be published. The conference will enhance the capacities of local communities to act on behalf of their environmental and other basic rights and sustainable livelihoods, as well as support international network
ing of the environmental movement in Sri Lanka. Centre for Environmental Justice (CEJ) was established in January 2004. CEJ aims to protect the equal environmental rights of the people, conserve nature and natural resources, support ecologically sound comm
unity activities, promote good environmental governance and ecological sustainability. CEJ provides free legal advice to the people affected by environmental problems, campaigns against e.g. environmental pollutants and climate change, and raises awareness
 on environmental impact assessment processes and the environmental outcomes of development initiatives. CEJ is a member of the Friends of the Earth International and functions as the Friends of t
Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland

title: Travel Support: Presentation of Final Evaluation Report
description:
As a research-funding partnership of three Canadian government agencies, the Global Health Research Initiative (GHRI) brings people together from different countries, sectors, and areas of expertise to tackle the complex global health problems. GHRI funded the Teasdale-Corti Global Health Research Partnership Program, which closed in 2012. This project will provide funding for Dr Sanjeev Sridharan to present the final program evaluation in Ottawa to the funders: 
- Foreign Affairs, Trade and Development Canada
-Canadian Institutes of Health Research (CIHR)
-IDRC

The Evaluation Centre for Complex Health Interventions at the University of Toronto designed the evaluation in collaboration with IDRC and CIHR.

Evaulating the Teasdale-Corti research
The Teasdale-Corti program's objectives were to:
-foster international partnerships and collaboration to promote the generation, communication and use of relevant health research in low- and middle-income countries (LMICs);
-train and support researchers responsive to LMICs' health policy and practice priorities; and,
-promote active collaboration between researchers and research users to support health priorities in LMICs.

Its four program areas included: health policy and system research, prevention and control of pandemics, prevention and control of chronic diseases, and interactions of health, environment, and development.

IDRC's Evaluation Unit assessed the evaluation as being of good quality. The evaluation provides more than 20 recommendations at three levels: the program's theory of change, future versions of the program, and associated calls for proposals. The presentation will allow GHRI to share the learning and results of this evaluation.

title: Development Policy Support Program II
description: The proposed loan for the second DPSP (DPSP-2), which is subprogram 1 of the proposed program cluster, building on the support provided through the first DPSP approved by the Asian Development Bank (ADB) in December 2005. The DPSP seriescofinancing the Development Policy Loan (DPL) series supported by the World Bank and the Government of Japanis embedded in the Governments Medium-Term Development Plan (RPJM) for 20042009. It supports the broad goal of the RPJM to stimulate higher and sustainable economic growth (to 7% average annual growth by 2009 from around 4% prior to 2004) and halve poverty (from 16.6% in 2004 to 8.2% by 2009). To achieve these goals, DPSP-2 supports wide-ranging reforms in four core areas to (i) improve macroeconomic stability and creditworthiness, (ii) promote investments, (iii) strengthen the public financial management and anticorruption framework, and (iv) improve the delivery of public services. DPSP-2 is proposed as a single tranche operation based on a range of up-front actions taken by the Government in the core areas.

title: PMS IN201714220170519000000
description: Award Description - The description for this item is INM-EOP

Centro Campesino de Asesoría y Capacitación Integral Juntos en el Camino, A.C.'S agriculture and vermicompost project will address the following issues: 1. Indiscriminate use of agrochemicals in food production, coupled with the existence of few spaces that promote ecological agriculture 2. Lack of access to organic, quality and low cost soil amendments, ultimately causing negative repercussions on the environment and health of communities.  Project Activities: 1. Install an automated sprinkler system in the vermicompost production model. 2. Improve the infrastructure for storing compost. 3. Train team responsible for the production of vermicompost. 4. Standardize the method of production and enrich the product with microorganisms. 5. Establish an agreement with Colectivo Campesino Estero Libre and PIAP to exchange knowledge and tools. 6. Create a vegetable farm and mango orchard as a demonstration plot and training space for farmers. 7. Conduct research through laboratory studies on vermiculture products to determine its components and nutritional value. 8. Promote ecological agriculture among farmers in the region. 9. Maintain a regular production of vermicompost so that producers have access at an affordable cost. Project Goals: 1. Improve the infrastructure, methods and sustainability of CECACI to produce vermicompost, at a high quality and low cost, promoting its use among farmers in the region to reduce the indiscriminate use of agrochemicals and promote ecological agriculture 2. Farmers in the region will be able to access an alternative space in food production to obtain advice, training and acquire soil amendments will help reduce the use of agrochemicals and improve yields and production costs. 3. The reduction of agrochemical usage in the community to substantially decrease ecological damages and improve community health. 4. Raising family incomes and the nutritional quality of foods by incorporating organic inputs.
Centro Campesino de Asesoría y Capacitación Integral Juntos en el Camino, A.C.

The program's strategies include empowering girls, creating access to good quality education and SRHR services, creating economic opportunities, changing norms and creating an enabling community and policy environment.

title: University Scholarship Program (USP) VII-LAU
description: (Lebanon):  USAID will continue to fund scholarships to academically meritorious yet financially disadvantaged students through a $17.8 million cooperative agreement to the Lebanese American University (LAU) in September 2015.  This funding will provide full scholarships to at least 174 students over the next eight years.  The first cohort of 73 scholars was enrolled as of August 2016; another cohort of around 74 students is expected by September 2017.  The USP VII is a continuation of a cooperative agreement awarded in 2015, and available money will incrementally fund the mechanism to continue the scholarship support. As directed by Congress, the expansion to include private schools is planned in the new scholarship mechanism that is being currently designed for award by September 2018. This program attributes to the higher education earmark and is directed by the Congress.

title: Union to Union Syd- och Östram 2014-2016 och Ram  2017
description:
SAMMANFATTANDE BESLUTSSKÄL

Union to Union (f.d. LO-TCO Biståndsnämnd) ansöker om rambidrag för 2017 på 135,1 MSEK för projekt och programverksamhet i utvecklingsländer och Östeuropa, inklusive administrations- och vidareförmedlingsbidrag där den totala budgeten uppgår till 153,0 MSEK inklusive en egeninsats på 14 %. Ansökan avser en ettårig förlängning av den verksamhet som genomförs under avtalsperioden 2014-2016. Vid en jämförelse av det sökta beloppet för 2017 och anslaget för 2016 på 119,9 MSEK (enligt andra avtalsändring av underavtal daterat 2016-11-21) motsvarar det ansökta beloppet en ökning på knappt 13 %. Union to Union förklarar ökningen främst med hänvisning till ett par gemensamma faktorer inom verksamhetens 11 sektorer. Den första rör valutakurser, där den svenska kronan tappat i förhållande till både CHF (Swiss Franc) och USD. Den andra faktorn är förknippad med att deras samarbetsparter drabbats av att andra givare dragit ner sitt stöd till den fackliga verksamheten medan behoven har kvarstått. Därutöver lyfter man att det krympande utrymmet för civilsamhället att verka innebär större utmaningar än tidigare. I ansökan för 2017 finns också ett par nya initiativ föreslagna i form av ett policyprogram avseende Agenda 2030 och den fackliga rörelsen (1 MSEK) och en s.k. Innovationsfond (0,5 MSEK) med syfte att kunna möta oförutsedda behov under året.

Union to Unions vision för verksamheten är att det i alla länder finns oberoende, demokratiska och jämställda fackliga organisationer som har kapacitet att företräda sina medlemmars intressen. De vill uppnå detta genom att arbeta med erfarenhetsutbyten och utbildning i fackliga och mänskliga rättigheter i arbetslivet, ledarskap inom fackliga organisationer, arbetsmiljö, jämställdhet, social dialog och hiv/aids.

Sida beslutar att bevilja Union to Union 120 MSEK för verksamheten 2017. Skälen är följande:

	Sida bedömer att Union to Union är en viktig aktör inom det fackliga arbetet och stödet till arbetstagarorganisationer i utvecklingsländer genom sitt globala nätverk av fackliga organisationer (Global Union Federations) och sin plattform i Sverige genom de svenska medlemsorganisationernas fackförbund. 

	Sida bedömer att den i ansökan 2017 föreslagna verksamheten är relevant under strategin Stöd genom svenska organisationer i det civila samhället 2016-2022 (CSO-strategin) eftersom att den relaterar till strategins övergripande syfte "att arbeta för ett livskraftigt och pluralistiskt civilt samhälle i utvecklingsländer" och till strategins båda övergripande målområden, dvs. 1) Stärkt kapacitet hos det civila samhället i utvecklingsländer och 2) Främjande av ett gynnsamt samhällsklimat för civilsamhället i utvecklingsländer. 

	Union to Union har varit ramorganisation till Sida sedan 1977 och Sidas erfarenhet av samarbetet med Union to Union är överlag god. 

	Då ansökan avser en ettårig förlängning av den verksamhet som genomförs under avtalsperioden 2014-2016 bedömer Sida att nivån på anslaget för 2017 bör ligga på ungefär samma nivå som anslaget för 2016. Givet den samlade bilden på anslaget bedömer Sida att Union to Unions ansökan om höjt anslag på ca 13 % inte föranleder Sida att höja anslaget för 2017. Sida föreslår att bidrag till den s.k. Innovationsfonden inte beviljas då presenterat underlag inte uppfyller kraven i Sidas insatshanteringsregel. 
 
BEREDNINGEN AV ANSÖKAN

Då ansökan för 2017 avser en förlängning av verksamheten under avtalsperioden 2014-2016 bereds insatsen som ett kompletterande insatsbeslut. Sida har därför i så stor utsträckning som möjligt utgått från den beredning som gjordes av ansökan för avtalsperioden 2014-2016. I den utsträckning som denna bedömts vara fortsatt relevant har bedömningen behållits och endast en kompletterande kommentar gällande 2017 har lagts till. I vissa fall, är bedömningen som gjordes i beredningen av den förra ansökan inte längre relevant, varför en ny bedömning har gjorts. Insatshanterings

title: Energy Community of South East Europe APL Program - APL 5 for Albania DAM SAFETY
description: The development objectives of the Fifth Phase of Dam Safety Project in Support of the Energy Community of South East Europe Program Adaptable Program Loan are to: (i) contribute to safeguarding the major hydroelectric dams of Albania; and (ii) improve their operational efficiency and enhance the stability of power supply for the regional electricity market. The AF2 will also provide Technical Assistance support to continue modernization of the project implementing entity's dam safety department, supervision's engineer implementation support, the independent panel of experts contract, and implementation of an updated financial management system at the project's implementing entity.

title: Humanitarian assistance through WFP to the Syria crisis incl. the response in Syria and the region
description:
Support to WFP Syria crisis operations both in Syria and regionally. World Food Programme (WFP) is the UN programme for food assistance and has a central role in all humanitarian crises globally and is one of largest channels of Finnish humanitarian fundin
g. The Syrian humanitarian crisis affects a growing number of the country's 21.4 million population. In the beginning of October 2013 the number of Syrian refugees amounted to 2.1 million and 4.25 million people were internally displaced in Syria. Approxim
ately half of the refugees and people in need are children. The total need of humanitarian assistance including the Syria Humanitarian Assistance Response Plan (SHARP) and the Syria Regional Refugee Response Plan (RRP) is 4.4 billion USD which is about one
 third of the global humanitarian needs in 2013 and the largest UN appeal in history. WFP's share of the appeals is a total of 1.132 billion USD i.e. approximately a quarter of the total appeal. WFP's operation inside Syria reaches about 3 million people i
n need per month and the WFP regional operation has approximately 2.6 million beneficiaries.
Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland

title: International Research Chairs Initiative (IRCI)
description: The International Research Chairs Initiative (IRCI) is a partnership between IDRC and the Canada Research Chairs (CRC) program. IRCI seeks to create opportunities for chair holders from low- and middle-income countries and in Canada to implement joint research programs, create unique training and fieldwork opportunities for students, and identify new avenues for knowledge, policy or technology transfer. Through an open and peer-reviewed competition, the initiative will support up to five IDRC research chairs in eligible universities. Each IDRC research chair will define a five-year program in collaboration with a Canada research chair in one or more of IDRC's four program areas: Environment and Natural Resource Management; Information and Communication Technologies for Development; Innovation, Policy and Science; and Social and Economic Policy. Proposals will be evaluated in terms of their relevance to one or more of the aforementioned four thematic areas; the demand for comparative research in that area; and the potential for mutually beneficial collaboration. It is expected that the IDRC research chairs will play a key role in addressing development challenges and mentoring the next generation of scholars and practitioners.

title: Even it Up Campaign in Vietnam Phase 2
description:
Inequality is the central to Oxfam#s mission to fight poverty. Vietnam is one of more than 40 countries where Oxfam is developing anational inequality campaign. The inequality campaign in Vietnam runss from 2016 to 2019. The four-year campaign focuses on promoting public debates on the need to combat extreme inequalities, raising public awareness of the issue, enhancing the roles of CSOs in addressing inequalities and contributing to discussions and the progressive changes policies that address inequalities. The long-term goal of the campaign is that by 2019 there will be improvement on policy development/execution (or legislative change/policy change) to fight inequality and more effective re-distributive measures to address poverty and gender injustice. This will be backed up by solid evidences that extreme inequality is wrong, and stands in the way of people claiming their rights.

The 1st phase of  the EiU campaign in Vietnam (2016-2018) has conducted several studies on inequality in Vietnam as well as people's perception on this issues. These studies have provided important input to campaign activities which have succeeded in  increasing people's awareness on the general concept of inequality and the need to tackle it. This next phase (2018-2019)of the campaign will specify the issue of inequality so that citizens can feel its relevance, practise the values of equality as well as advocate for the changes in policies that will solve the causes of inequality and sustainable reduce the gap between the richest and  poorest group.  This phase aims to create a discourse on inequality in the society and bring solving inequality into the government's agenda.

Oxfam is seeking to make the progress on three areas towards meeting this goal which are as follows:

- Shifting the debates and creating the new discourseamong the policy makers, media and citizen to make greater change possible from now until 2019. The debate will include the increasing gap between the rich and the poor, state budget mobilisation through the fair fiscal system with the focus on women and girls, labors' rights
- Inspire youth led campaign groups  and CSOs to pay attention to inequality and support to enhance their roles in addressing inequality in public
- Policy progress about the inequality in accessing quality social services (health) through more transparent and accountable information sharing mechanisms about state budget mobilisation and allocation to social services.

Expected outcomes:
- A comprehensive campaign strategy to direct the communication activities in 2018 and 2019
- An established equalitycoalition empowered to promote equality values and changes in policies to tackle inequality.
- Discourse on inequality/equality becomes common in social debates, academic sphere and political space.

This campaign will work closely with other stakeholders within the Financing for Development Programme such as BTAP, M.net, Tax Justice Alliance to make greater impact.

reporting.org: Directorate-General for European Civil Protection and Humanitarian Aid Operations (ECHO)
title: WASH assistance to conflict affected returning communities of North Waziristan Agency (NWA), FATA
description: The action, led by NCA with PADO as implementing partner, will address emergency WASH needs of the most vulnerable returnees in 3 tehsils of NWA of FATA. As per UNOCHA, out of 5 million persons who were displaced from FATA and KP, more than 90% have returned to their places of origin. NWA is one of the most affected FATA agencies with 190,219 extremely vulnerable individuals (women, children and others) within the returning IDPs, with more returnees expected in 2018.Rapid Needs assessment in the field by NCA/PADO in Nov 2017 helped to validate the secondary data. The proposed humanitarian action will provide WASH assistance to support 30,002 of the most vulnerable returnees including 500 children in 10 schools and 5000 Out Patient Department (OPD) patients in 5 health centers in 11 villages of 3 tehsils - Mir Ali, Miran Shah and Spinwam in NWA. By ensuring a more hygienic environment, the action will improve health outcomes related to poor WASH conditions and practices such as the incidence of cholera and diarrhea.This will be done in a participatory manner by rehabilitating 4 communal and 15 institutional water supply schemes (WSS) and constructing 280 latrines in households, schools and health centers (including 50 latrines for persons with disabilities). The repair of WSS and latrine construction will be undertaken. The provision of technical advice and supervision by NCA and partner staff will also enable the beneficiaries to meet their other emergency needs for future shocks. Targeted beneficiaries will be encouraged to adopt improved hygiene practices, including menstrual hygiene management, throughschools campaigns and training of health workers. The action is in line with the WASH cluster guidelines and focuses on returnees who have not received any or inadequate WASH support.
Directorate-General for European Civil Protection and Humanitarian Aid Operations (ECHO)

title: Ecohealth Emerging Infectious Diseases Research Initiative (EcoEID)
description: New infectious diseases, mostly of animal origin, are emerging more rapidly than ever. Southeast Asia is the current hotspot of disease emergence due to high population and animal densities, on the one hand, and relatively limited (human and animal) healthcare delivery capacity, on the other. This project aims to understand the relationship between emerging infectious diseases of potentially pandemic proportions, and the agricultural, land utilization and ecosystem management practices that give rise to them. The project will begin with a competition in Southeast Asia for funding multi-country studies coordinated by an institution or consortium of institutions located in the region. The emphasis will be on capacity building, networking and policy impact at the regional level. Lessons learned from the Southeast Asian experience will inform similar activities in other regions such as South Asia, West Africa and Egypt.

title: DCCN Stateless Children and Women Groups Empowerment Project 2016-2020
description:
The Stateless Children and Women Groups Empowerment Project under Development Center for Children and Community Network supports stateless students and stateless women with approximate number of 3,748 and 2,198 people respectively including indirect target groups of 128,562 stateless people in 3 provinces of Chiang Mai, Mae Hong Son and Tak. The stateless students and women are having problems on personal legal status and citizenship, making them not equally access to rights to education, health care, travel, scholarship and decent work. Major causes of the problems are their lack of knowledge and understanding on personal legal status verification processes, ineffective enforcement of the law by authorities and unavailability of necessary law and policies.
The project aims to get their names registered with 13 digits identification number in order to access the government services such as rights to education, health care, travel and decent work and that they are equally treated. 
The project objectives are that the students and their families receive the highest legal status and are able to access their rights.
The project expects the students including their families to obtain legal status including nationality for a minimum number of 300-500 persons per year in 4 target districts including other register offices.
Activities include data survey and development, training for stateless student’s volunteers and women groups, mobile counseling services, legal clinic, stateless women group empowerment, coordination with authorities in relevant district offices, network building at targeted communities and policy advocacy.
Focus thematic areas are statelessness and personal legal status and citizenship and women empowerment.
Other stakeholders include government sectors such as district office, NGO’s such as legal status networks.
Development Center for Children and Community Network

title: Women's Voice and Leadership - Ethiopia
description: This project is part of Canadas Womens Voice and Leadership Program, which supports local and regional womens organizations and networks that are working to advance womens empowerment and gender equality in developing countries. This is done by supporting their activities, building institutional capacity, and promoting network and alliance-building as womens and feminist organizations are critical agents of change. The Program also responds to the globally recognized, significant gap in funding and support to womens organizations and movements around the world.  The project is implemented by Plan International Canada. It has been designed to provide womens organizations (WOs) with the capacity, resources and opportunity to realize their mission and vision, address their organizational challenges, promote efficiencies in programming, and create a platform for coordinated advocacy and networking. The project directly supports 48 WOs across four regions of Ethiopia (Amhara, Addis Ababa, Oromia and, Southern Nations, Nationalities, and Peoples' Region) and indirectly supports up to 148 civil society organizations (CSOs). The project also provides training and support to 72 young feminists.
Foreign Affairs, Trade and Development Canada

title: WCM 2016-2020
description:
Project Title: Shan Communities’ Equal Rights Opportunity & Access Project
Aim: Men and women enjoy equal rights, opportunities, access to information, and government services in Northern Shan State.
Objective: By end of 2020, 3,184 men and women in 16 ethnic villages in two townships have improved capacity to lead their own development and improved access to health and social services.
Problem Analysis: For women; lack of opportunities, lack of social protection, lack of women’s self-help competences, lack of access to health care in combination with their reproductive role, stereotypes the ‘people’ have and the domination of men are root causes for gender inequality.
For ethnic groups; the following root causes contributed to ethnic inequality whereby minority groups are marginalized: lack of opportunities, lack of social services, lack of awareness on ethnic rights, not being included in business opportunities as well as being dominated by Burmese and fearing to lose their ethnic identity.
Result 1: Community Health Workers and Health Insurance Funds are functioning.
Result 2: SHGs are functioning and members completed business training and started individual or group business.
Result 3: VDC’s completed training on leadership skills, PCM, community organizing, human rights, gender, land law and developed VAPs.
Result 4: Community, in particular youth, has improved awareness on safe migration, acquiring legal documents and trafficking.
Result 5: Local Partner Organizations have improved capacity.
 Main activities and Thematic priorities:
-       Basic health services, including pregnant and lactating mothers, nutrition, family planning, HIV/Aids and TB awareness
 -       Social services, including Self-Help Groups and small business support
 -       VDCs capacity building and village action planning (land use planning and DRR planning)
 -       Community awareness, including land rights, safe migration, youth migrants, legal documents and exploitation/ trafficking
 -       Capacity building LPO

title: SWE-2010-63 Exploring the link between environmental stress and communal conflict
description: The project aims at exploring the effect of environmental stress on the occurrence and dynamics of communal conflict. It will employ disaggregated, cross-national statistical methods using new and unique data on communal conflicts combined with comparative case studies from Benin, Mali and Nigeria. Studying interactions between environmental stress, demographic, political and economic factors and communal conflict, it will provide insights into the effect of environmental stress on social conflicts. It will thus provide knowledge that is crucial for the prevention and management of armed communal conflict in an era of climate change.

title: Regional Public Financial Management - Pacific
description: The Regional Public Financial Management initiative, provided through the Australian Department of Finance and Deregulation, aims to improve public financial management legislation, policies, systems and processes in Pacific Island countries. Funding will support: strategic development training for up to 20 senior finance managers;  PEFA assessments and roadmaps for public financial management improvements; technical input to regional public finance management education and training through the University of the South Pacific; support for a major public finance management project in a selected Pacific Island country each year; engagement and networking of senior finance officials as part of the Pacific Island Financial Managers Associations; and support for the 'Canberra Group' meeting which is a forum to support the dissemination of public finance management development assistance information, expertise and experience. The total value of this initiative is $3.9 million over 4 years, starting 2012-13.

title: Stop the Cycle of HIV: Support Women and Children!
description: Across Uganda, hundreds of thousands of women are living with HIV. Without the proper support, HIV positive mothers will give birth to HIV positive babies, making an AIDS-free Uganda an impossibility. This project will help Alive Medical Services, a medical centre in one of Kampala's poorest neighborhoods, support women and children with free HIV treatment. By donating, you will have an impact not only on the lives of our patients, but on the lives of families and communities as a whole.

reporting.org: Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation, Spain
title: Proyecto Alas Abiertas, danza para niños y jóvenes con discapacidad, necesidades educativas especiales y desventaja social
description: ALAS ABIERTAS, es un proyecto de acercamiento a la danza a niños/as y jóvenes con discapacidad y necesidades educativas especiales en Paraguay, posibilitando que puedan incluirla entre sus posibilidades de formación y expresión artística. El proyecto se desarrolla en la capital como en el interior del país. Durante todo el año escolar, participan de Talleres de Danza Contemporánea dirigidos por un equipo multidisciplinario compuesto por bailarines-pedagogos y docentes de danza con formación en educación especial y psicología. Es también un proyecto de Formación de Formadores para profesionales y docentes del área artística, bailarines y estudiantes vinculados e interesados en aplicar el arte como herramienta educativa. Al final del periodo Muestra de Talleres de Danza en el CCEJS en Asunción. A través de la puesta en escena de un espectáculo de danza, los niños/as y jóvenes se aproximan a la experiencia de mostrar el trabajo realizado y compartir con otras personas la alegría que experimentan danzando. Dos veces al año se desarrollan Clases Abiertas en cada uno de los centros educativos. Familias, amigos, vecinos, compañeros y agentes locales conocen de esta manera, el proceso de trabajo que profesores y alumnos desarrollan a diario en el aula. Actualmente itineran en diferentes muestras y festivales audiovisuales en América y Europa, dos proyectos desarrollados durante el periodo 2007-2008. En la exposición fotográfica -Prohibido llover en primavera- y el video danza -El prado- los protagonistas son algunos de los niños/as y jóvenes participantes del programa de talleres de danza. Alas Abiertas organiza la asistencia a espectáculos de danza y colabora en participación y presencia en diferentes eventos culturales de los participantes del proyecto. En Madrid, el proyecto se desarrolla en Residencias de Menores de la Comunidad de Madrid, siguiendo la metodología del proyecto en Paraguay.

title: Strategisk Fond 2015-2016
description:
Sektionskontoret för utvecklingssamarbete och sedermera ambassaden har sedan 2009 haft en Strategisk Fond. Syftet med fonden är att finansiera mindre initiativ som är strategiska för genomförandet av strategin för utvecklingssamarbete med Kambodja, men som faller utanför ramverket för de större insatserna inom respektive resultatområde/sektor. 

Initiativ som finansieras via fonden är förstudier inför eventuella beredningar, utvärderingar, seminarier, studieresor, översättningar och publikationer. Fonden finansierar kostnader för flygbiljetter, visum,språktester och översättning i samband med kambodianst deltagande i Sidas International Training Programme (ITP), samt ramavtal för revisionstjänster som faller utanför de revisioner som avtalats med samarbetspartners, inklusive systemrevisioner och tolkning av revisionsrapporter. 

Varje enskilt initiativ (komponent i PLUS) bör vara begränsad i tid och i sin utformning och kopplad till tydliga resultat. 

The purpose with the Strategic Fund is to to finance smaller initiatives which are strategic for the the implementation of the Development Cooperation Strategy for Cambodia, but that fall outside the framework of the larger contributions in the respective result areas/sectors. 

Initiatives that can be financed through the Strategic Fund are preparatory studies prior to possible assessments, reviews and evaluations, study visits, translations and publications. The Strategic Fund finances costs for air travel, visa application, English tests and translations in connection with Cambodian participants in Sidas International Training Programmes (ITP), and frame agreements for audit services that fall outside the regular audits that have agreed with the cooperation partners, including system audits and interpretation of audit reports. 

Each individual initiative (component) should be limited in time and scope, and have clear expected results. 

The procedures for the Strategic Fund are as follows: 
1) The Programme Administrator is responsible for the overall management of the contribution. 
2) The Programme Officer writes a separate decision for a PLUS component in word format 
3) The Programme Officer is responsible for follow-up of the components 
4) The decision and documentation is archived under Strategic Fund.

title: Lutte contre le mariage des enfants
description:
Ce projet fait partie dun programme global de protection de lenfant de lUNICEF intitulé « Making Benin a safer place for children to grow »  et qui se construit autour de cinq 5 axes : trafic des enfants, travail des enfants, violence contre les enfants, enregistrement des naissances et la justice pour les enfants. 
Pour aborder le mariage des enfants, ce programme préconise une approche intégrée qui cible le renforcement du système de protection de lenfant afin de pouvoir mieux prévenir et répondre à la violence et lexploitation, y compris les mariages des enfants. Il contribue également à améliorer loffre et la qualité des services de protection en veillant à lapplication équitable des politiques et législations protectrices et en sassurant que les enfants aient accès à la justice, à léducation et aux services sociaux. Le projet « Lutte contre le mariage des enfants au Bénin » vise la prévention du mariage des enfants au Bénin par le renforcement du système de protection de lenfant, la promotion d'un environnement légal et politique favorable, l'autonomisation des filles, le renforcement des capacités et la mobilisation des enfants, des jeunes, des parents et des membres de la communauté et un meilleur accès des filles à une éducation de qualité.
Directorate-general Development Cooperation and Humanitarian Aid

reporting.org: Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland
title: Organisational Support for the Finnish Refugee Council
description:
The Finnish Refugee Council is a specialist in international refugee work. Its mission is to improve the basic rights of refugees and returnees. As an associate of the UNHCR in Finland the Council is a religiously and politically independent development co
operation organisation. Founded in 1965 the Finnish Refugee Council has been involved in development cooperation work globally providing adult education and youth welfare services in refugee camps in a range of countries. The Council also supports returnee
 communities in societies recovering from crises. In Finland the Council?s roles are mainly informational educational and social. The Finnish Refugee Council?s information services offer background information on international refugees and raise awareness 
about refugees and their lives both in global crisis areas and in Finland. The services also provide information on the work of the Finnish Refugee Council. Fundraising is also a fundamental aspect of the Council?s work. Donations are used for the organisa
tion?s work and are channelled to address the world?s refugee crises through the UNHCR.In 2013 Finnish Refugee Council was selected to receive programme support of the Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland including its development education and informat
ion work. In addition the Council receives organisational support for its general activities.
Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland

title: ACCESO DE AGUA POTABLE Y EMPODERAMIENTO DE LAS MUJERES EN LA REGIÓN DE KANDI (BENIN) - CONSTRUCCIÓN DE UN POZO
description: ACCESO DE AGUA POTABLE Y EMPODERAMIENTO DE LAS MUJERES EN LA REGIÓN DE KANDI (BENIN) - CONSTRUCCIÓN DE UN POZO :: El proyecto surge de la necesidad perentoria de acceso al agua de las localidades de Banikani agravada en los últimos años por la extrema sequía, de la urgencia de mitigar el alto nivel de analfabetismo de las mujeres de la zona y de mejorar las condiciones sanitarias, y de implantar la tradición en la gestión de bienes públicos (comités de gestión de pozos), impulsando estrategias orientadas a ampliar las oportunidades de desarrollo de su población a partir del aumento y mejora de las necesidades sociales básicas de la población en situación de pobreza y exclusión. En particular, la contraparte enfoca su trabajo en la atención de las necesidades específicas de las mujeres. Se trata de la región más pobre del país por causa de las condiciones climáticas e hidrográficas desfavorables.

Introduktion: 
Plan Sverige har inkommit med en ansökan om rambidrag på sammanlagt 452 000 000 kr för en 3,5-årsperiod som börjar i januari 2015 och fortsätter till 30 juni 2018. Anledningen till att avtalsperioden föreslås vara 3,5 år är att Sida har ställt sig positivt till att anpassa avtalsperioden och rapporteringsschemat till Plan Sveriges brutna räkenskapsår. Budgeten för verksamheten ligger på en högre nivå än tidigare år, och ett godkännande av den föreslagna budgetnivån skulle innebära en höjning av rambidraget med drygt 28 procent (från drygt 101 MSEK per år till 130 MSEK per år). Sida bedömer att ökningen är välplanerad och bygger på styrkorna i tidigare program. Ansökan är skriven i enlighet med instruktionen för stöd under Strategin för stöd genom det svenska civilsamhället. Sida bedömer att ansökan är komplett och att verksamheten är relevant i förhållande till strategin.

Ansökande organisation:
Plan Sverige är en del av den internationella barnrättsfederationen Plan International som har verksamhet och landkontor i över 50 länder i Afrika, Asien och Latinamerika. Plan Sverige grundades 1997 och är en av 21 nationella organisationer i Plan-federationen. Plan Sverige är en stiftelse (inte en medlemsorganisation). Däremot har organisationen ett starkt nätverk av faddrar som varje år bidrar med mer än 60 procent av organisationens budget. Medlen från fadderverksamheten ger Plan (både internationellt och i Sverige) en stabilitet som ger möjligheter att fastanställa personal oberoende av eventuell kortsiktighet hos givare, samt betala för budgetposter som tidvis är svåra att samla in medel till. Plan Sverige har varit ramorganisation sedan 2006 (förnyad ramstatus 2014) och Sidas samlade erfarenhet av ramsamarbetet är god. På senare år har organisationen även fått status som strategisk partner för Sidas humanitära enhet och ECHO-status för samarbete med EU i humanitära frågor. 

Plan Sverige har under de senaste åren stärkt sin personalstyrka, och närmare 20 personer är på olika sätt delaktiga i att hantera ramanslaget. Av dessa är sju regionsamordnare, fem tematiska rådgivare, en programekonom, en verksamhetscontroller på heltid (ny tjänst), chefer, samordnare av institutionella givare och administrativ personal.

Plan Sverige samarbetar med Plan Internationals landkontor för insatsen, och landkontoren fungerar både som vidareförmedlare till civilsamhällesorganisationer och som genomförare av delar av programmet. Beredningen av insatsen har i största möjliga mån försökt bedöma landkontorens kapacitet i båda dessa roller. 

Sida bedömer att Plan Sverige fortsatt är en relevant partner i ramsamabetet med kapacitet att hantera ramanslag från Sida.

Ansökan:
Ansökan för perioden 2015-2018 har till syfte att "barn och ungdomar, tillsammans med civilsamhället, kräver sina rättigheter från ansvarstagare som aktivt engagerar sig för att respektera, skydda och uppfylla dessa rättigheter" (fritt översatt). Verksamheten ska ske i 19 länder, fyra regionala initiativ samt ett globalt program för påverkansarbete och innovation. Plan Sveriges ansökan är i stort en fortsättning på den verksamhet som organisationen haft under de senaste fyra åren under två avtal: Ramavtalet och avtalet gällande regeringens satsning på barns och ungdomars rätt till hälsa och utbildning. Nuvarande ansökan har för första gången helt integrerat de två ansatserna, och har resulterat i fem tematiska resultatområden/program:

1. Barns och ungdomars rätt till skydd från våld
2. Barns och ungdomars rätt till sexuell och reproduktiv hälsa
3. Barns och ungdomars medborgarskap och samhällsstyrning
4. Barnrättsstyrning
5. Barns rättigheter i katastrofsituationer (riskförebyggande och motståndskraft)

Sida bedömer att programmet är väl sammansatt, bygger på Plan Sveriges och Plan Internationals styrkor och på väl beprövande metoder - tillsammans med en vilja att hitta innovativa sätt att nå ännu bättre resultat.

Sida bedömer att Plan Sveri

title: Getting Out of the Middle-Income Trap in Peru: New Partnership for Better Policies
description:
While Peru experienced an unprecedented economic boom from 2004 to 2013, approximately 7 million Peruvians continue to live in poverty. This project will address the problem by assessing and testing public policies that can drive productivity and competitiveness.

Gaps persist despite growth
Poverty has declined substantially in Peru, but continues to affect 20% of the population. It is primarily concentrated in rural and remote regions. One in four Peruvians lives in these areas, and almost half of them are poor. Economic growth has failed to reduce gaps in opportunities for the country's young citizens, and its rural and indigenous women. This has caused a middle-income trap. The economic slowdown and the downward trend in investment will make the situation worse.

Testing policies for change
The July 2016 change in government and parliament offers an opportunity to address social gaps. This project will support collaboration among researchers, central and regional governments, and the private sector in Peru. Together, they will assess and test public policies to drive productivity and competitiveness. The goal is to promote innovative economic, social, and environmental policies.

The project will also enhance technical and financial collaboration between the 48 research institution members of the Peruvian Consorcio de Investigacio¿n Economica y Social and the National Council for Science and Technology. These organizations are working to develop applied social research and quality data for effective policy interventions at the national and local levels.

title: Logis de Louvranges
description:
The reception centre has been opened for 5 years and shelters women and children while they receive specific accompaniment throughout the asylum application process to help prepare them for their new life. 21 independent private apartments allow for a community life in a former convent which alleviates the isolation of these women.

Thanks to its strong experience in welcoming asylum seekers, Caritas International was well placed to identify the specific needs of women migrants who experiment extreme difficulties once they find themselves unprotected and outside of their country of origin. They carry a heavy past since many of them had to flee their country faraway from their relatives either because they were victims of violence, armed conflicts or discriminations. Traumatized and isolated, they had to bear the exile, the constraints of asylum application, the financial distress while trying to go beyond their traumatism and to take care of their health and children.

Website: http://www.caritas-int.be/fr/page/les-logis-de-louvranges; http://www.caritas-int.be/fr/activity/logis-de-louvranges

title: GlobalGAP certified helda beans
description:
The applicant, Bakker Barendrecht BV is the main supplier of fresh vegetables and fruits to Albert Heijn, and other AHOLD companies in Europe. For the supply of helda beans (snijboontjes or runner beans) Bakker Barendrecht BV is dependent on produce from Morocco and Spain. Because the Helda bean is sensitive to warm and cold, and Morocco and Spain have cold winters sometimes, the quality and quantity of beans from these countries is not always sufficient. Therefore, Bakker Barendrecht BV has explored possibilities to start production in Senegal.

Local partner, Safina SARL, is a family owned company and produces (amongst others) French beans for Bakker Barendrecht BV / Albert Heijn. The partners have done successful tests on a small scale and results are promising.

In European winters, there is a high demand and low supply of helda beans in the Netherlands. Therefore prices are relatively high in this period. The partners will form a joint venture to start producing helda beans for this period on the farm of Safina SARL, just outside Dakar. The beans will be cultivated in 20 modern plastic greenhouses of 1 ha each.

The project will employ 162 people (partly part-time) and most seasonal (6 months per year). It is estimated that this corresponds with 69 FTE on annual basis. The operation will be BSCI and GlobalGAP certified. It is expected that other companies in the sector will follow producing these beans, after the pilot turns out to be successful. The project is also positive for Senegal's negative trade balance, as the helda beans are cultivated for the export market.

description:
The purpose of the Program is to support the development of a sound and broad-based financial sector that effectively channels resources to productive investment. Specifically, the Program will seek to: (i) reduce the cost of borrowing and expand access to credit by improving the framework for secured transactions, (ii) protect depositors from poor governance practices in banks, (iii) enhance the role of the non-bank financial (NBF) sector in savings mobilization for investment capital, and (iv) improve investor confidence by reducing the risks from potential money laundering through the financial system.

The Program has three main components: (i) banking sector; (ii) NBF sector; and (iii) Anti-money laundering (AML) regime. The banking sector component will aim to reduce the cost of borrowing and expand access to credit by facilitating debt enforcement and lowering the cost of collateral registration. This component will also introduce legal and regulatory changes to strengthen corporate governance in banks and to improve the supervision of groups and conglomerates that control financial institutions. The NBF sector component will seek to enhance the sector's role in resource mobilization and allocation by developing the legal and regulatory framework, strenghening regulatory capacity through the establishment of a single regulator for NBF sector, the Nonbank Financial Regulatory Commission (NBFRC), and strengthening corporate governance and transparency. This component will also aim to reduce the distortionary impact of tax policies on the financial sector. The AML component will seek to mitigate the potential risks from money laundering activities by supporting the development of the legal and regulatory framework for the AML regime, and the establishment of a financial intelligence unit to monitor and report suspicious financial transactions.

reporting.org: Directorate-General for European Civil Protection and Humanitarian Aid Operations (ECHO)
title: Protection and Life-Saving Assistance for Disaster-Affected Internally Displaced Persons in Ethiopia.
description: An increasing number of individuals in Ethiopia are affected by recurrent disasters. The International Organization for Migration (IOM), since 2007, has been operating in Ethiopia assisting migrants and internally displaced persons (IDPs) to save and restore their lives. This project, launched in April 2017, aims to save lives and contribute to the protection of IDPs in Ethiopia through: 1) enhancing information management on disaster and displacement, 2) providing life-saving and protective emergency shelter (ES) and non-food items (NFI) to displaced persons through both in-kind and cash-based & voucher assistance, 3) establishing/strengthening referral mechanisms through coordinated effort with Protection Cluster and CP/GBV sub-cluster to ensure protection needs of most vulnerable IDPs, 4) supporting the most vulnerable migrant returnees from KSA forced deportation, 5) ES/NFI ALERT funding for newly displaced flood-affected populations, and 6) Site Management Support (SMS) and life-saving Water, Sanitation & Hygiene (WASH) interventions to support Gedeo and West Guji internally displaced persons. The ALERT funding announced in May 2018, incorporated as Result 4, addresses the immediate life-saving ES/NFI needs of 10,000 HH beneficiaries (55,000 individuals) in the context of recent widespread flooding. The current displacement in Gedeo and West Guji is occurring in the context of a large humanitarian caseload of existing IDPs in Ethiopia. IOM's Displacement Tracking Matrix (DTM) Round 10 conducted in March/April 2018, identified 1,613,436 internally displaced persons of which, 1,073,764 are displaced due to conflict and 488,090 due to climate induced displacement (Annex 1). In relation to these on-going and expected crises, IOM launched a Crisis Appeal 2018 for Ethiopia, outlining 88.5m (Annex 2)

title: OCHA 2014 - 2017 (incl. ProCap, GenCap och UNDAC)
description:
Detta beslut är ett kompletterande insatsbeslut till avtal med OCHA om bidrag till humanitära insatser, och gäller år 2017. Beslutet tas i enlighet med Sidas insatshanteringsregel paragraf 3.11.3. och avser det fjärde året av Sidas avtal med OCHA för stöd till humanitär fältsamordning (2014-2017). Avtalsperioden förlängdes i januari 2016 till 30 oktober 2018 i syfte att säkerställa att det sammanfaller med OCHA:s strategi (Strategic Framework) för 2014 - 2017.

Sida har redan i 2016 beslutat och avtalat om SEK 96 000 000 för 2017. Genom detta beslut görs ett tillägg på SEK 4 000 000, vilket innebär en sammalagd finansiering på SEK 100 000 000 för 2017. Även fördelningen av stödet mella land- och regionkontor samt tekniska program görs genom detta kompletterande insatsbeslut och bilagt avtalstillägg. 

Sida bedömer att samtliga medel för 2017 ska utbetalas omgående för att möjliggöra planering och uppstart av årets verksamhet. Ett avsteg från Sidas vanliga rutiner om uppdelade betalningar bedöms motiverat.

Bedömningspromemorian har skrivits på engelska med anledning av att engelskspråkig personal i fält är delaktig i beredning och uppföljning av insatsen, i enlighet med generaldirektörens beslut om Sidas språkvalsmatris med tillämpningsanvisningar från den 1 mars 2013. 

-------------

År 2017 beräknas över 100 miljoner människor vara i behov av humanitärt stöd. För att säkerställa ett snabbt, effektivt och behovsbaserat stöd krävs en stark humanitär samordningsmekanism som påvisar effektivitet även i de svåraste miljöer. UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) har enligt generalförsamlingens resolution 46/182 detta mandat och har visat i stor utsträckning kunna leverera denna samordningsuppgift genom sina kontor i 50 länder, 9 regional kontor och högkvarter (i Geneve och New York). 

På landnivå är OCHA:s mandat att a) samordna behovsbedömningsprocessen i varje land så att en enhetlig behovsanalys produceras, b) samordna den humanitära responsen i varje land. OCHA ansvarar för att säkra samordning mellan sektorer, hantera information, stödja en samlad uppföljning av responsen, resursmobilisering, och stödja den humanitära samordnaren (HC) i sitt arbete. OCHA har även ett specifikt ansvar att säkra integrering av övergripande frågor såsom gender och skyddsfrågor, vilket görs bl.a. genom de OCHA-administrerade GenCap och ProCap -programmen. 

Huvudsyftet med insatsen är att stödja OCHA i sitt uppdrag att implementera sitt samordningsmandat stipulerat i Resolution 46/182. Detta mandat konkretiseras vidare genom "OCHA Plan and Budget 2016". Huvudsyftet med stödet är att stödja Mål 1 "Field Effectivenes", med följande delmål: 
1.	Stärkt humanitärt ledarskap
2.	Harmonisering och koordinering av behovsbedömningar
3.	Gemensam humanitär responsplanering, implementering och uppföljning 
4.	Flxibel och anpassningsbara koordineringsstrukturer
5. Skydd för och tillträde till drabbade befolkning 

År 2017 tilldelas OCHA:s landkontor, regionala kontor samt tekniska program sammanlagt 100 MSK (varav detta beslut avser 4 MSK) med följande fördelning: 

För lankontor sammanlagt 78 MSEK: Afghanistan 3,5 MSEK, CAR 4 MSEK, DRK 7 MSEK, Irak 3 MSEK, Mali 4 MSEK, Niger 4 MSEK, Tchad 4 MSEK, Kamerun 4 MSEK, Palestina 2 MSEK, Somalia 4 MSEK, Sydsudan 5 MSEK, Sudan 2 MSEK, Jemen 5 MSEK, Colombia 1 MSEK, Etiopien 2 MSEK, Myanmar 2 MSEK, Pakistan 2 MSEK, Syrienkrisen (inkl. kontoren Syrien, Turkiet, Jordanien, Libanon) 10 MSEK, Philippines 1 MSEK, Ukraina 1,5 MSEK, Haiti 1 MSEK, Nigeria 4 MSEK, Libyen 1 MSEK, Burundi 1 MSEK.

För regionala kontor sammalagt 13 MSEK: Västra Afrika 4 MSK, Östra Afrika 2 MSK, Mellanöstern och Norra Afrika 2 MSK, Asien 4 MSK, Stilla havet 1 MSEK. 

För tekniska program sammanlagt 9 MSEK: GenCap 4 MSK, ProCap 3 MSK, and UNDAC 2 MSK.

Ovan fördelning sker på basis av Sidas behovsbaserade humanitära allokeringsmodell.

title: Improving Performance of Cattle Production
description: Indonesian demand for beef is rising by 4% each year, with this increase and a substantial amount of supply met through imports. Indonesias Government has placed a high priority on achieving self-sufficiency in beef cattle production. Increasing production depends on smallholder enterprises, located in densely populated rural areas, boosting reproductive rates of cows and improving management techniques to accelerate the fattening of animals so that they can be sold at market sooner. To achieve these objectives changes to traditional feeds of rice straw combined with small amounts of crop residues and supplements are needed. Using a systems approach combining on-station and on-farm trials, mixes of high quality feeds to fatten animals and traditional feeds to maintain weight gain and body condition will be trialled.
Australia - Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade

description: Award Description - The description for this item is Pakistan

title: Livestock Against Poverty and Dependency in Post-Conflict Georgia
description: This project will provide assistance to families living in Tkviavi village, which was greatly affected by the August 2008 conflict between Georgia and Russia. Many of the families in the area are former internally displaced people who fled to the cities of Gori and Tbilisi at the height of the conflict. Since returning, many families found much of the livestock in the village was killed or stolen, and many of the houses were burned. There is a shortage of fodder and most of the areas orchards were destroyed. Due to the threat of active landmines, crops cannot be harvested. It will take several seasons to restore agriculture production. Livestock and dairy production is one of the few jobs that offers returning farmers the chance for economic and social security. By becoming involved in dairy production, participants will gain access to much-needed nutrients and pursue opportunities to earn money. Farmers will also re-enter the market through production and sale of cheese and other milk products. In the first year of the project, Heifer International will provide at least 150 families with 150 local breed Caucasian brown breed heifers. An additional 150 families will benefit from passing on the gift in the third year of the project. An additional 25 families in the community will benefit from participating in project trainings. In addition to providing training to all project participants, GRM International will set up a winter-feeding program for all recipients of cattle, as well as provide instruction and necessary equipment to produce, market and sell cheese.

title: F.a: Strengthening Community Conservation Resilience in Africa and the LDCs
description:
The project supports indigenous peoples? organisations or other CSOs working with local communities in five countries (Democratic Republic of Congo, Ghana, Kenya, Nepal and Tanzania) in implementing a participatory assessment on the resilience of indigenou
s peoples? and local communities? biocultural approaches and biodiversity conservation as well as restoration initiatives. In addition, capacity-building events will be organised on the participatory assessment methodology developed by the CCRI. The Uganda
n NAPE will provide technical support to the actors implementing the assessments, and organise meetings for the new leaders of the communities, which have participated in the CCRI previously in order to support them in implementing the agreed recommendatio
ns. The preliminary findings of the at least 15 assessments to be implemented will be documented in five national reports. An advocacy campaign will be implemented during the UN Biodiversity convention?s Conference of the Parties in December 2016 in Mexico
 in order to disseminate the CCRI findings. The main findings of the assessments will also be disseminated within the involved communities and to the broader public through for instance social media, leaflets and radio programmes. The project aims at promo
ting more effective and appropriate forms of legal, political, technical, financial and other support that can address the most important internal and external threats to the resilience of community conservation. There is increasing scientific and politica
l acknowledgement of the significance of indigenous peoples? and local communities? conservation and restoration initiatives to the protection of biodiversity and climate change mitigation as well as resilience. The initiatives face, however, both external
 and internal threats, and there is lack of sufficient analysis on the support needed by the communities. Resilience assessments carried out by the communities enable presenting their own alternatives to strengthening the resilience. Project beneficiaries 
include indigenous peoples and local communities implementing collective biodiversity protection and restoration initiatives. During the project 100 community representatives trained on the participatory assessment methodology are expected to reach 7 500 p
eople in 15 communities, in which the assessments will be implemented. Gender equality and women?s participation will be paid particular attention to during the assessment processes.
Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland

description: General objective: Guarantee the enjoyment of the rights to protection, development, reintegration and participation of children and adolescents at risk, associated with armed groups and otherwise affected by the armed violence in Colombia, through prevention of driving factors and by bringing the consequences of the armed conflict for children onto the peace agenda. description:
Krisen i Sahel er i høj grad en fødevarekrise. I Sahel-området i det nordlige Afrika er 80 pct. af al dyrkbar landbrugsjord påvirket af ørkenspredning. Det skaber massive fattigdomsproblemer for de mennesker, der bor i de berørte områder. Jorden kan ikke længere bruges til landbrug, og millioner mister deres livsgrundlag. Specielt i landene Niger, Chad, Sudan, Burkina Faso og Mali melder både UNICEF og WFP om stigende fødevareusikkerhed på grund af tørke og høje fødevarepriser. I Mauretanien vurderer WFP, at omkring 700.000 mennesker er ramt af alvorlig fødevaremangel, sammenlignet med 500.000 i de foregående år. Uregelmæssigheder i regnmængden, særligt i det østlige Sahel, har resulteret i store tab i høstudbytte og enorme græsningsarealer, der ligger afsvedne hen. 
Med bidraget til UNICEF bidrages der til at øge modstandskraften hos lokalbefolkningerne på tværs af Sahelbæltet og på at forberede sig strategisk på dårlig høst med fejlernæring og sult til følge i 2012. Bidraget vil gå FN fødevareprogram så fødevareberedskabet i Mauretanien, Mali, Chad, Niger, Burkina Faso og Senegal.

title: Fortalecimiento de redes de protección de defensoras/es de DDHH de la región Oriente de Guatemala
description: El proyecto persigue fundamentalmente, fortalecer la conformación y fortalecimiento de las redes de Protección de Defensoras/es de derechos humanos, así como a la implementación de acciones encaminadas a mejorar las medidas de protección hacia defensoras/es y medidas específicas para las defensoras. Traslado de capacidades para la implementación de planes de seguridad y acompañamiento legal en casos de defensores criminalizados. Además se visibilizará el estado de situación de las defensoras/es en el país, impulso de campañas en medios de comunicación social locales y nacionales en relación al trabajo que defensoras/es desarrollan. El proyecto se centrará en la región oriente del país, en los departamentos de Zacapa y Chiquimula, en los cuales por su posición geoestratégica coincide con los intereses privados tanto nacionales como transnacionales, quienes han intentado impulsar megaproyectos para la construcción de un canal seco, explotación de recursos híbridos y forestales. Esta región, por su posición cercana a puntos fronterizos también experimenta problemas de tráfico de personas, drogas, narco ganadería, entre otros impulsados por estructuras del crimen organizado, quienes son poderosas en distintos puntos de la República guatemalteca.

title: Implícate (Educación en la solidaridad, iniciación al voluntariado y la cooperación)
description: "Implícate (Educación en la solidaridad, iniciación al voluntariado y la cooperación) :: El proyecto se desarrolla principalmente en 8 centros educativos deNavarra, ubicados en diversos barrios de la ciudad de Pamplona y de municipios cercanos a la capital,contando con su compromiso y aval de participación. Esta iniciativa consiste en iniciar y acompañar procesos que realice alumnado de 4º de la ESO y 1º de Bachillerato. A través de 3 talleres dinámicos de sensibilización en las aulas, acerca de las desigualdades sociales existentes en nuestro entorno y en países del Sur, y presentando la solidaridad como eje de alternativascomo el decrecimiento o el comercio justo, se reta a los y las jóvenes que quieran participar, a pensar y realizar actividades solidarias en beneficio de personas y grupos más desfavorecidos, apoyando iniciativas de la ciudad de Pamplona en torno a diversos Días Internacionales. Esto les motiva y pone en marcha sus capacidades personales en torno a una causa común, poniendo en juego lo que ellos y ellas saben y pueden hacer; sus riquezas personales. Las actividades tendrán un componente solidario y de denuncia. Y el objetivo final está centrando en la necesidad de crear soberanía popular, que la ciudadanía tenga conciencia de la necesidad de su implicación y participación social para poder alcanzar ese otro mundo posible. El mayor valor del proyecto no son las actividades en sí mismas, sino el proceso experiencial de desarrollo de valores, habilidades y actitudes que realizan los y las jóvenes: solidaridad, participación, protagonismo, emprendiduría, diálogo, equidad de género, responsabilidad, esfuerzo, creatividad, alegría, asertividad, autoestima, sociabilidad, interculturalidad, conciencia crítica, justicia, democracia, no-violencia, etc. Hemos seleccionado a la juventud como destinataria teniendo en cuenta uno de los principios de Fundación Adsis: ?trabajo con y para los y las jóvenes?. De hecho, la educación en valores de los y las jóvenes y su formación como personas en la sociedad es un tema que preocupa tanto a los centros educativos como a las instituciones y sociedad en general. Fundación Adsis cuenta con una amplia experiencia en la puesta en marcha de proyectos de Sensibilización y Educación para el Desarrollo en centros educativos de todo el estado.En Navarra llevamos trabajando en diversos centros educativos desde el año 2010, y con este proyecto queremos consolidar las relaciones establecidas hasta el momento así como iniciar relaciones nuevas con otros centros. Debemos decir que este proyecto se ha llevado a cabo en Barcelona con financiación de su ayuntamiento y se han obtenido unos resultados muy positivos, tanto es así, que el proyecto se ha publicado en la Guía de Buenas Prácticas del Ayuntamiento de Barcelona."

title: Niger - The Kandaji Ecosystems Regeneration and Niger Valley Development Programme (KERNVDP)
description: Le programme de régénération des écosystèmes de Kandadji et de développement de la vallée du Niger (KERNVDP) est conçu pour apporter des solutions à la sécheresse récurrente au Niger et à la dégradation des ressources naturelles. En effet, le programme Kandadji est une priorité pour le pays, qui le programmait depuis très longtemps mais ne pouvait le mettre en uvre en raison de contraintes sociopolitiques, techniques et financières. Le principe du programme est de soutenir le débit minimum du fleuve Niger, d'atténuer la dégradation des écosystèmes, de garantir un approvisionnement en eau constant aux villes (Niamey et Tillabéri), de fournir de l'eau pour l'irrigation le long de la vallée du fleuve et, enfin, de produire de l'électricité. Sa mise en uvre consiste en la construction dune structure de régulation du débit du Niger afin de fournir leau nécessaire à lirrigation et à dautres utilisations essentielles (alimentation en eau potable, assainissement, écologie, cultures de décrue améliorées, pâturage et pêche), ainsi que sous forme de sous-produit qui rendra la structure aussi rentable que possible. La première phase couvrira la période 2009-2014 et coûtera 186,23 millions d'UC.
Haut Commissariat au Barrage de Kandadji

title: Strengthening Primary Health Care System In Northern Darfur-Kutum Locality
description:
The
project is designed to contribute to the achievement of the long-term goal of
the health and nutrition recovery strategy for Darfur; Progressively
restructure the health and nutrition arena, now a patchwork of disparate
elements that emerged in response to multiple stressors, into a coherent,
effective, efficient and equitable service delivery system. The identified gaps and deficiencies are significant
and addressing them constitutes a giant endeavor. Taking into account the limiting factors such as poor
implementation capacity fo the stkeholders, and hostile environment (insecurity and unpredictable
instability), a sequenced/three-pronged health nutrition recovery strategy for
Darfur has been endorsed by the MOH and DRA.



The
project is in line with many measures included into the first
prong health recovery strategy. Maximizing the outputs of existing health and
nutrition services by filling gaps, upgrading assets, expanding services,
boosting productivity, and improving quality of health services is the overall
objective of proposed project. And thus meeting the basic human rights of the community. 



The
focus will be on infrastructure rehabilitation, as well as functional upgrading
of health facilities with the heaviest workload and closer to vulnerable,
conflict affected population settlements. 

The selected site is the one where the needs are the
highest, the implementation will positively impact on the largest number of
vulnerable people, there is safe access to enable the implementation,
supervision and monitoring, and they are included into the Darfur health
recovery plan (Government commitment). The planned interventions for the
achievement of the project goal include: 1. Quality health services and facilities accessed by
approximately 25,000 people in the Northern Darfur State, specifically Kutum Locality.2.Basic maternal and child health care services
enhanced in Northern Darfur state through training midwives to reduce maternal
and infant mortality and improve postnatal care

title: Author's Workshop: Building an Indian State for the 21st Century
description:
India is demonstrating immense potential and capacity to contribute to the global economy, security, and development. It has emerged as one of the world's largest democracies. Its economy is growing. It is also an important regional power in Asia.

However, considerable weaknesses in its state institutions persist, restricting the country's ability to generate inclusive economic growth and political stability. Many state institutions, such as the judiciary, police force, public administration, and diplomatic corps, remain critically understaffed. They struggle to provide public services, and governance weaknesses are hampering them. 

This project will help improve our understanding of how Indian state institutions can function more effectively to support inclusive economic growth and political stability. Researchers will examine capacity gaps in key Indian state institutions. They will propose ways to strengthen human capital and institutional performance. The project team will work closely with Indian think tanks and senior government officials to ensure the findings are relevant.

More specifically, the project will support a three-day author's workshop to:
- bring together researchers to develop a multi-year research framework focusing on India's core state institutions; and,
- support the development of new papers on the capacity of India's state institutions. 

The chapters will be included in an updated and expanded edition of the book, Public Institutions in India: Performance and Design (Oxford University Press).
University of Pennsylvania Institute for the Advanced Study of India
University of Pennsylvania Institute for the Advanced Study of India

title: Appui à l'intégration socio-économique des réfugiés centrafricains du site de Gaoui au Tchad.
description: S'appuyant sur l'expérience acquise lors du projet de réinsertion socio-économique des retournés tchadiens de RCA du site de transit de Gaoui (ECHO/-AF/BUD/2016/92053), ACTED propose par cette intervention d'en répliquer les modalités pour l'intégration des réfugiés centrafricains du même siteEn effet, de nombreuses familles réfugiées et d'origine tchadienne installées en RCA ont été rapatriées au Tchad suite à de violents affrontements qui ont éclaté à Bangui en 2013. En 2017, ACTED a pu participer à la réinsertion de 3 321 retournés tchadiens du site de Gaoui mais n'a pas pu apporter son soutien aux 553 réfugiés également présents. L'action proposée entend donc fournir une assistance intégrée pour la sortie volontaire des réfugiés du site de Gaoui. Pour ce faire, ACTED viendra favoriser l'accès des ménages à un logement digne et décent, et renforcer durablement les moyens d'existence de ces populations. Enfin, REACH soutiendra la conduite d'un exercice de collecte de données afin de pouvoir informer les échéances humanitaires importantes (HNO), en complément et synergie d'autres initiatives existantes.
Directorate-General for European Civil Protection and Humanitarian Aid Operations (ECHO)

title: Utvärdering kapacitetsutveckling genom ITP
description:
Insatsen gäller en extern utvärdering av ITP (internationella kapacitetsutvecklingsprogram) som ett av Sidas verktyg för kapacitetsutveckling. Syftet med utvärderingen är att ge en aggregerad analys av tidigare utvärderingar och studier som relaterar till ITP som kapacitetsutvecklingsinstrument, vidare skall utvärderingen kritiskt bedöma och analysera antaganden och design av ITP, samt den metodutvecklingen som skett över tid. 

Utvärderingen förväntas ge rekommendationer kring hur Sida kan vidareutveckla det nuvarande ITP- verktyget i linje med aktuell forskning inom kapacitetsutveckling, samt ge förslag på om och hur andra globala kapacitetsutvecklingsprogram kan komplettera och / eller ersätta den nuvarande modellen. 

Den primära användaren är Sida / CAPDEV som avser att använda denna utvärdering för lärande och förbättring av Sidas angreppssätt. Utvärderigen kommer dessutom att användas i processen med att utveckla och operationalisera den kommande strategin för kapacitetsutveckling 2018-2021. 

Utvärderingen skall i huvuddrag utföras i linje med bifogat uppdragsbeskrivning och avropssvar.

title: AUC: 2015-2017 Trade & Industry Programme
description:
Afrikanska Unionen fastställer och övervakar genomföradet av gemensamma afrikanska principer och åtaganden. Afrikanska Unionen är det enda organ som har ett politiskt mandat att på pan-Afrikansk nivå trycka på för förbättringar genom att arbeta för alla medlemsländer och regionala ekonomiska gemenskaper.
 
Avdelningen för handel och industri (DTI) vid Afrikanska Unionens Kommission (AUC) har mandat att bidra till att hela Afrika integreras till ett enda handelsblock och blir en stor och konkurrenskrafting handelspartner i den globala ekonomin genom tätt samarbete med medlemsstaterna, de regionala ekonomiska gemenskaperna och andra intressenter. Medlemsstaterna och de regionala ekonomiska gemenskaperna har arbetat, och arbetar fortfarande, med skapande och utformandet av de regionala ekonomiska gemenskaperna för att fördjupa samarbetet och harmoniseringen inom varje regional ekonomisk gemenskap (dvs aktiviteterna inom varje regional ekonomisk gemenskap som omnämns i Abuja-avtalet). Tiden är emellertid inne för att öka ansträngningarna på pan-Afrikansk nivå (dvs mellan de regionala ekonomiska gemenskaperna ) att uppnå en bredare och mer harmoniserad ekonomisk integration på kontinenten. Med sitt Pan-Afrikanska mandat och sin räckvidd är AU den mest lämpade aktören att ta den regionala integrationen ett steg vidare (dvs mot ett Pan-Afrikanst frihandelsområdet, tullunion och slutligen monetär union), framförallt genom koordinering och harmonisering av handelsregler och procedures (tullar och icke-tariffära handelshinder) mellan de regionala ekonomiska gemenskaperna. 

I den Afrikanska Unionens nuvarande Strategiska plan (2014  2017) ska arbetet inom handel och industri fokusera på att både öka handeln inom Afrika och Afrikas andel av den globala handeln, bl.a. genom att etablera (underlätta förhandlingar för att uppnå) ett kontinent-övergripande frihandelsavtal för bredare och djupare regional integration på kontinenten, vilket bl.a. innebär ökad harmonizering av handelspolitik och lagar, förbättrad implementering av Handelsproceduravtalet som framförhandlats under Världshandelsorganisationen (WTO). Målet är att det ska leda till förenklade handelsprocedurer mellan medlemsstaterna, ökad produktiv kapacitet och bättre infrastuktur samt uthålligt utnyttjande av kontinentens naturresurser.

I linje med AUCs strategiska plan (ovan) kommer Sveriges stöd till AUC DTI 2015 att fokusera på ett speciellt projekt som heter "Stöd till genomförandet av WTOs handelsproceduravtal" vilket i sin tur innebär stöd till genomförandet av en "gap och behovsanalys" och därefter utformning av en strategi för hela Afrikanska Unionen rörande genomförandet av WTOs handelsproceduravtal på kontinenten. 

Det föreslagna stödet är mycket relevant i förhållande till både Afrikanska unionens och Sveriges strategiska prioriteringar samt de slutgiltiga mottagarna, dvs AU:s medlemsstater och regionala ekonomiska gemenskaper. Dessutom kompletterar det föreslagna stödet det stöd som andra givare ger.

title: Polioimpfprogramm XI
description: Die FZ Maßnahme umfasst die Linien X&XI, die gemeinsam zugesagt wurden, jedoch aufgrund der verschiedenen Finanzierungsformen unterschiedliche BMZ Nummern und somit auch Datenblätter erhalten haben. Die Maßnahme soll das indische Poljoimpfprogramm im Rahmen der globalen Bemühungen zur Poliobekämpfung unterstützen, die Übertragung und Zirkulation des wilden Poliovirus zu unterbrechen, damit das Land in absehbarer Zeit von der WHO als poliofrei zertifiziert werden kann. Zwischenzeitlich konnte die WHO diese Zertifizierung ausstellen. Ziel der Maßnahme ist; - die landesweite Impfung aller Kinder unter 5 Jahren mit einem oralen Polioimpfstoff sowie - die erfolgreiche Umsetzung eines landesweiten Polioüberwachungssystems zur Erfassung aller Fälle von akuter schlaffer Lähmung (Acute Flaccid Paralysis, AFP- Surveillance), um die Voraussetzung für einen schnellen Einsatz von Nachimpfkampagnen in Gebieten mit potentiellen Neufällen zu schaffen. Die Unterstützung beinhaltet insbesondere die Beschaffung der benötigten Impfstoffe für die jährlich mehrfach durchgeführten nationalen sowie subnationalen Impfkampagnen in 2008/09 (EUR 44,58 Mio.) sowie, in geringem Umfang, die Beschaffung von Laborausrüstung und Verbrauchsgüter für den Aufbau des Polioüberwachungssystems (EUR 0,50 Mio.). Programmträger ist das indische Gesundheitsministerium. Die Beschaffungen erfolgen jedoch über UNICEF (Impfstoffe) und WHO (Laborausrüstung). Die FZ-Maßnahme Ist abgeschlossen. Die Gesamtkosten des indischen Polioimpfprogramms für den Zeitraum 2008/09 betrugen geschätzte EUR 442,49 Mio. statt wie ursprünglich geplant EUR 443,00 Mio. Die bereitgestellte Finanzierung aus der Poliolinie XI (FZ-Darlehen) in Höhe von EUR 13,58 Mio. konnte vollständig umgesetzt werden. Die Zuschussmittel der Linie XI wurden vollständig gekürzt (siehe Datenblatt 2008 10 048). Die Bundesregierung unterstützt im Rahmen der Finanziellen Zusammenarbeit seit 1996 das indische Polioimpfprogramm. Die Unterstützung ist Teil des deutschen Beitrags zur Global Polio Eradication Initiative (GPEI).
Bundesministerium für wirtschaftliche Zusammenarbeit und Entwicklung (BMZ)
