title: Malawi - Karonga-Chitipa Road Project
description: The Karonga-Chitipa Road Project aims to improve rural road infrastructure development in Malawi. It should support the local economies of the Chitipa and Karonga districts by reducing the transportation cost of agricultural and industrial products of the region, and reducing travel time between the two district centers. The proposed road should improve transport services between Malawi and Zambia, and contribute towards the promotion of regional integration. The output of the project will be a two-lane 47.3-km bitumen surfaced road with 6.7-meter carriageway and 1.5-meter wide sealed shoulders on both sides, between Lifilya and Chitipa, as a section of the Karonga-Chitipa road. The project comprises the following components: (i) construction works for the upgrading of the existing gravel surfaced road to bitumen standard with 6.7-meter carriageway and 1.5-meter wide sealed shoulders on both sides for a total length of 47.3 km between Lifilya and Chitipa; (ii) consultancy services for supervision of construction works, and (iii) project audit services.

reporting.org: Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation, Spain
title: FORMACIÓN DE CAPITAL HUMANO EN LA ACCIÓN CULTURAL Y REFUERZO DE LA BIBLIOTECA DEL CENTRO LERCHUNDI DE MARTIL
description: Desde que abrió sus puertas en el curso 1996-97, podemos decir que el Centro se ha ido haciendo con el paso del tiempo, en continuo crecimiento, desde los comienzos humildes hasta la realidad consolidada de la actualidad. Planteada como un complejo de propuestas diversas, la Biblioteca Universitaria constituye su principal actividad, por su espacio, ubicación geográfica, ambiente de recogimiento que ayuda al estudio y su apoyo bibliográfico. Además posibilita la celebración de diversos actos culturales y sociales, tanto durante el curso lectivo como durante el verano. Esta misma razón impulsó acondicionar el salón grande para multiusos, sobre todo proyecciones de cine, talleres, matinales?Las aulas educativas se ubicaron en la planta alta del crucero y acogen a un profesorado multiétnico. Es decir, el Centro se proyecta como una realidad intercultural, pues participan estudiantes y colaboradores de diferentes nacionalidades, así como un equipo de dirección también internacional. Su objeto es la promoción de los jóvenes de esta región de Marruecos, a través de iniciativas formativas e informativas, de apoyo al estudio o la investigación, el incentivo a la creatividad, el asociacionismo civil, el diálogo o el encuentro y dando oportunidades laborales a licenciados en paro que se hacen cargo de los diferentes cursos de lenguas. La filosofía del Centro se rige por lo valores humanistas de la responsabilidad, esfuerzo personal, el servicio y compromiso con los demás y el trabajo comunitario. Nuestra Biblioteca se concibió en un principio como apoyo a la comunidad universitaria de las Facultades de Letras ubicadas en Martil. Desde hace dos años se han incorporado nuevas licenciaturas a la sede de Martil de la Universidad Abdelmalek Essaadi, en concreto la Facultad Polidisciplinar imparte las licenciaturas de Derecho, Económicas, Psicología y Sociología, Ello ha traído consigo un cambio de perfil del universitario que estudia en Martil, pues se ha diversificado enormemente la procedencia de los mismos ?de otras regiones de Marruecos-. Muchos de los nuevos estudiantes que acuden a la Biblioteca o piensan utilizar nuestros servicios demandan libros en dichas nuevas especialidades, demanda que no podemos satisfacer al no disponer de dichos fondos. Se precisaría incorporar libros, en las materias de literatura árabe, filología inglesa y francesa, economía, derecho, historia, informática y estudios islámicos, en lengua árabe y francés. Mucho Licenciados se incorporan a nuestro equipo de profesores y colaboradores, pero adolecen de la debida formación, más si cabe en la atención a la biblioteca y sus numerosos usuarios. Por ello se precisa la formación suficiente y necesaria en las materias propias de la Biblioteca: biblioteconomía y archivística, técnica

title: Canadian Community of Practice in Ecohealth : Training and Awards Program for Research in International and Development Settings
description: IDRC's Ecosystem Approaches to Human Health (Ecohealth) program initiative has been gradually devolving its awards program to southern institutions under the umbrella of communities of practice in Ecohealth (COPEHs). Training awards programs are now offered by COPEHs in West and Central Africa (Université du Bénin), Latin America and the Caribbean (Instituto de Salud Pública de Mexico), and East and Southern Africa (University of Kwazulu-Natal, South Africa). Researchers in key academic institutions have identified a need to consolidate efforts to build excellence and develop capacity in Ecohealth research. This grant will support the creation of a Canadian Community of Practice in Ecohealth (COPEH-Can) to promote and support Ecohealth research, education, policy and practice. COPEH-Can will be built progressively on a regional consortium of institutions that have demonstrated their interest in Ecohealth and have a strong record of collaborating with developing country scientists, mainly: the Université du Québec à Montréal (UQAM), the University of Guelph and the University of British Columbia (UBC). Over the next three years (2008-2010), each university will establish a regional node (Quebec/Maritimes, Ontario and BC/Prairies/Territories, respectively), and design and accredit a short graduate-level course in Ecohealth for students and professionals interested in international and development applications. The project will provide a pan-Canadian platform to deliver and manage up to five Canadian Ecohealth graduate awards per year. It will also facilitate knowledge exchange and partnerships with southern COPEH's.

title: Forumteater för förståelse av relationella processer för klimatanpassning i Kenya och Moçambique
description: Miljöstyrning präglas av komplexa problem där en mängd sociala och ekologiska faktorer samverkar. Dessa problem visar vikten av mänsklig förståelse för de sociala och ekologiska relationer och processer de är en del av. Trots detta vilar nuvarande policyverktyg ofta på hypotesen att människor styr över passiva ekosystem. Men för att förstå miljöförändringar, och särskilt klimatpåverkan, är det nödvändigt att tänka på människan som förankrad i dessa relationer och processer. I sammanhang relaterade till utvecklingsländer är det viktigt att ta hänsyn till hur klimatförändringar är knutna till ett flertal ekonomiska och politiska utmaningar och konflikter för att främja utveckling och hållbarhet.Syftet med det här projektet är att inkorporera relationella och processorienterade perspektiv som en viktig bas för att utforska de hinder som fattiga kustsamhällen står inför i strävan mot hållbarhet genom resursstyrning och välbefinnande. Utöver detta kommer relationsperspektivet hjälpa oss att identifiera möjligheter till gemensamma åtgärder som samhällen kan uppnå genom sina nätverk. Vi kommer att utforska dessa problem genom att utveckla forumsteater med lokalbefolkning i utvalda samhällen i Kenya och Moçambique. Projektet fokuserar på kustsamhällen i dessa länder som system där de sociala och ekologiska egenskaperna är djupt sammanflätade. Kustsamhällen är särskilt viktiga social-ekologiska system, där exempelvis fiske som grundläggande försörjning för miljontals människor runt om i världen har en mycket bättre position för att säkerställa en hållbar förvaltning av hav än industrifiske. Kustsamhällena präglas dock ofta av fattigdom, brist på politiskt inflytande för att få sina behov uppmärksammade och stor risk för klimatpåverkan. I detta projekt bygger vi på aktuell forskning kring dessa samhällen, där det framgår att beslutsprocesser inom fiske bättre förstås som en del av social-ekologiska nätverk. Genom detta projekt bygger vi på aktuell forskning kring dessa samhällen och på forskningsfronten för social-ekologiska system som en uppsättning relationer och processer som för samman sociala och ekologiska värden. Kustsamhällen  kan beskrivas konceptuellt som ett nätverk som för samman fiskarna, deras samhällen, försäljningsaktiviteter, redskap, fisk, båtar etc. Var och en av komponenterna i detta nätverk spelar en nödvändig roll för att upprätthålla samhället och utforska utvecklingsalternativ. Därför måste vi också dra slutsatsen att förändringar i nätverket påverkar kustsamhällena. För att testa relevansen av att konceptuellt beskriva social-ekologiska system på relationella sätt och utvärdera i vilken utsträckning de kan identifiera konflikter och främja stärkande handlingar kommer vi att utveckla samhällsteaterföreställningar, som bygger på kompetens hos projektdeltagare och kollegor. Vi kommer att utveckla föreställningarna tillsammans med lokala artister och samhällen för att försöka använda akademisk kunskap om de utvecklings- och hållbarhetsutmaningar som dessa samhällen möter. Detta bidrar till samhällenas egna reflektioner av sina erfarenheter relaterat till dessa utmaningar. Vi kommer använda metaforiskt tänkande för att (i) bättre förstå hur hindren för hållbar utveckling är djupt sammanflätade i social-ekologiska nätverk, och (ii) att förbättra en relationell uppfattning om social-ekologiskt handlande som ger samhällen ett reflexivt utrymme för att undersöka möjligheter för anpassning till klimatförändringar. Föreställningarna kommer vidare att representeras i flera samhällen genom forumteater, vilket är en slags teater där publiken kan delta och föreslår sätt att hantera de problem som representeras i föreställningen. Därefter kommer vi att efteranalysera dessa föreställningar i fokusgrupper med deltagare. Beslutsfattare, inklusive offentliga tjänstemän från lokal och nationell nivå, kommer att bjudas in till att delta från projektets början av två orsaker. För det första befinner sig kustsamhällen i svåra förhållan

title: Stichting Oxfam Novib
description:
Oxfam:
Oxfam is a leading organization in emergency WaSH and Food Security in Mozambique since 1987.  Over the past five years Oxfam has implemented WaSH responses to benefit flood-affected populations in Sofala and Zambezia, cholera-affected populations in Sofala and Niassa, WaSH activities for east African refugees in Cabo Delgado and Nampula, and EFSL response for populations affected by three consecutive years of drought in Gaza.  In Mozambique Oxfam uses a single programmatic approach, linking activities in sustainable livelihoods, humanitarian assistance, good governance and gender for amore effective impact on beneficiaries.  In 2013, in coordination with COSACA members, Oxfam with its local partners implemented an emergency intervention to benefit more than 32,000 people in nine of the most flood-affected communities in Gaza and 8,000people in Zambezia province through seeds and tools fairs, food security (EFSL) and access to safe water, sanitation and hygiene promotion (WASH).  The total funding mobilized was $2 million from the Oxfam co-federation network and two bilateral donors.

title: Think Tank Initiative End of Phase 1 - Opportunity Fund
description:
This funding will support Think Tank Initiative (TTI) grantees' organization-specific or collaborative efforts that contribute to achieving their long-term organizational goals. TTI-funded institutions had expressed the need for this funding in order to promote collaboration, learning, and innovation.

About the Opportunity Fund
In December 2013, TTI launched a call for proposals for the end of the Phase 1 Opportunity Fund. This fund supports TTI grantee organizations' efforts to achieve their long-term objectives. These are projects that cannot otherwise be carried out through use of TTI core funding. 

The purpose of the Opportunity Fund is to provide supplementary funding for activities that are not already budgeted for in the organizations' TTI work plans for 2013-2014. To be eligible for support, applicant TTI grantees will allocate and fully spend all their Phase 1 core funding by September 30, 2014.

Several TTI grantee institutions submitted research support proposals in response to the Opportunity Fund call. Selected proposals came from the following institutions:
-Fundación Dr Guillermo Manuel Ungo, El Salvador
-Fundación INESAD, Bolivia
-Foro Social de la Deuda Externa de Honduras, Honduras
-Instituto de Estudios Peruanos, Peru
-Fundación "ARU", Bolivia
-Fundación Salvadoreña para el Desarrollo Económico y Social, El Salvador

These proposals fulfill the call's requirements and comprise a variety of activities that will provide institutional support and foster collaboration among think tanks. 

The proposed activities include publications, capacity-building consultancies, and efforts to consolidate academic networks. In all cases, the activities align with each institution's objectives as listed in their TTI core funding grant agreements.

title: SMR Svenska Missionsrådet ram 2016
description:
Svenska Missionsrådet (SMR) har inkommit med en ansökan om rambidrag för 2016. 

ANSÖKANDE ORGANISATION
SMR är en svensk ideell förening och paraplyorganisation för 35 svenska samfund, missionsorganisationer och kristna biståndsorganisationer. Det är på dessa medlemsorganisationers uppdrag som SMR är avtalspart med Sida. SMR har varit ramorganisation under CSO-anslaget sedan 1980 och 2014-04-11 fattade Sida beslut om organisationens fortsatta ramstatus. SMR är en vidareförmedlande organisation, vilket innebär att en stor del av Sida-stödet förmedlas vidare till medlemsorganisationerna för deras utvecklingssamarbete. Utvecklingssamarbetet genomförs genom samarbetsorganisationer i utvecklingsländer inom olika tematiska och geografiska områden. Följande 17 av SMR:s medlemsorganisationer genomför och får stöd för utvecklingssamarbete under SMR:s övergripande ledning och ansvar:

ADRA Sverige
Evangeliska Frikyrkan
Erikshjälpen
Folk & Språk
International Aid Services (IAS) Sverige
KFUM Sverige
Kristna Fredsrörelsen
Vännernas samfund/Kväkarna
Lepramissionen
Life & Peace Institute
Operation Mercy
Svenska Alliansmissionen
Svenska Baptistsamfundet
Skandinaviska Barnmissionen
Svenska Bibelsällskapet
Equmeniakyrkan
Läkarmissionen (ny 2016)


ANSÖKAN
Ansökan avser en fortsättning på verksamheten under den pågående avtalsperioden 2013-2015. I enlighet med riktlinjerna för CSO-anslaget utgår ansökan 2016 från ansökan för 2013-2015 och fokuserar på förändringar och nyheter. Merparten av de policyer som legat till grund för verksamheten under 2013-2015 används och ligger fast även för 2016. En ny policy som tillkommit är dock policyn för rättighetsperspektivet som SMR antog under 2014. En medlemsorganisation, Individuell Människohjälp (IM), har lämnat SMR och en ny, Läkarmissionen, har tillkommit som medlem och bidragsmottagare. IM är nu ramorganisation och har ett avtal direkt med Sida. En nyhet i ansökan är också att SMR föreslår en pott för insatser med fokus på Disaster Risk Reduction (DRR). Fokus för verksamheten under 2016 kommer annars att vara att fullfölja, avsluta och utvärdera den verksamhet som pågått under 2013-2015 samt att planera verksamheten för den kommande femårsperioden 2017-2021. SMR avser att inkomma med en femårsansökan för denna period. I ansökan ingår totalt 60 insatser som genomförs i 50 länder av totalt 17 medlemsorganisationer och deras ca 129 samarbetsorganisationer. Insatserna varierar i storlek och komplexitet. Vissa är enstaka projekt med en partner i ett land medan andra är större program som genomförs i flera länder och med flera partner. 

I ansökan lyfter SMR specifikt hur de ligger till i relation till de dialogfrågor som följs upp i rapportering och dialog inom ramen för det pågående avtalet mellan Sida och SMR. Dessa frågor är 1) Vidareutveckling av rättighetsbaserat arbete, 2) Påverkansarbete på central/nationell nivå, 3) Hur miljöfrågor beaktas i verksamheten, 4) Hur utvärdering används strategiskt i verksamheten och 5) Arbete med tvärfrågor och baslinjer i relation till resultatmodellen. En ytterligare fråga som tillkommit är frågan om hur känsliga värderingsfrågor som t.ex. HBTQ och abort hanteras inom ramen för utvecklingssamarbetet. Dessa frågor har följts upp i beredningen. 

Sida bedömer att ansökan är väl sammansatt och att den ger en god bild av verksamheten. Sida har dock begärt in några kompletteringar, framför allt avseende förtydliganden av budgeten. Inför nästa ansökan bör Sida och SMR diskutera hur SMR kan ge ett tydligare underlag för Sidas budgetbedömning. Detsamma gäller resultatmatrisen som också skulle kunna vara tydligare presenterad. 


BUDGET I ANSÖKAN
SMR ansöker om ett totalt belopp om 162.870.000 SEK för verksamhet 2016. Detta är dock en avrunding nedåt jämfört med de detaljerade siffrorna i den bilagda budgeten. I budgeten uppgår de totala Sida-bidragen till 162.965.408 SEK och Sida utgår i budgetanalysen från denna siffra även om det ansökta

description: The development objective of Development Response to Displacement Impacts Project in the Horn of Africa Project for Uganda is to improve access to basic social services, expand economic opportunities, and enhance environmental management for communities hosting refugees in the target areas of Djibouti, Ethiopia and Uganda. title: Youth empowerment
description:
Objective
The main objective of this project is:
Young Dutch farmers support rural youth in developing countries in defending their interests, lobbying and in becoming rural entrepreneurs.

The secondary objective is:
Involve more Dutch young farmers in international cooperation.

Subgoals
	Motivate and help young farmers to set up their own Young Farmers Branch
	Support and advise on the design of youth policy
o	Training (the leadership and management skills) of young board members
o	Exchange experiences in how to organize and manage a farmers association 
o	Assist in lobby trainings and stay involved in lobby roadmap 
	Share knowledge on agricultural and marketing skills with individual young farmers
	Make sure the interests of rural youth from developing countries are taken into account at the (international) political advocacy 
o	Select and train NAJK-members involved in Agriterra assignments in intercultural communication and brainstorm methods
	Communicate Agriterra activities to Dutch young farmers in order to increase involvement.

Entrepreneurship
NAJK has members who are farmers in all kinds of different sectors; from animal production, milk production to horticulture. Most of them are involved in cooperatives or have alternative ways of selling their products. Becoming a farmer in the Netherlands is not an easy choice; farm installation is an expensive and long process. Most young people taking over a farm take this decision for life. It is their wish to be independent, to be an entrepreneur and to make a living out of their business. They are often eager to learn and have spend time at other farms (abroad). Most of them are far better educated than their parents. 

This drive to be an entrepreneur, their skills and their eagerness to learn can serve as an example for young people in developing countries. As in the Netherlands, rural work often has low status in these countries. Inspired by young Dutch farmers they can turn themselves into entrepreneurs as well. Dutch agro technical knowledge can serve in their education.   

Advocacy
NAJK as an organization has acquired a lot of knowledge over the years about business acquisition, advocacy, working with youth and managing projects . Board members speak regularly to EU-politicians in Brussels, national politicians like the Minister of Agriculture and local government bodies.  Over the years NAJK has build a large network of business companies, cooperatives, civil society and politics. NAJK is a respected partner for business and government where it concerns the interests of young farmers. Because NAJK is an organization for young people, board members cannot be older than 35 years and cannot be part of the board for longer than four years. NAJK is a breeding place for ambitious young people who would like to gain experience in governing and lobbying. Trainers and coaches make sure they acquire the right skills. As an organization NAJK has a clear vision, mission, a solid administration and professional staff members. NAJK feels dedicated to young farmers in less favorable conditions in developing countries. Organization building, lobbying and advocacy are activities in which NAJK can support young farmers in developing countries with .

Activities
a. A preparatory training weekend is organized for a maximum of fifteen NAJK-members that will be very likely to be assigned to facilitate a training / advisory assignment. This training is organized by the Institute of Cultural Affairs and involves:	Intercultural Communication
	Group Facilitation Methods (including the Focused Conversation Method and the Consensus Workshop Method)
b. A training for NAJK members having been assigned to missions and likely to be employed by Agriterra again. This training will be more in-depth and deal with the specific experiences of the Agripoolers . 
c. The farmers organizations in developing countries formulate their needs for training/advice and make a profile of the young farmers needing/participating the advice/training. This list including the profiles should be prepared as early as possible in order to prepare the assignment well. When already familiar with the organization, NAJK can make suggestions for the selection of participants.  
d. NAJK nominates candidates that are considered most suited for the assignment.
e. The selected candidate will be appointed to a NAJK-trainer/employee who will help to prepare the assignment in more detail. An NAJK-employee will help writing the report if necessary . 
f. In case of a visit to the Netherlands, a Terms of Reference including profiles of participants is delivered to NAJK as early as possible. NAJK-employees will be responsible for formulating and hosting a program . Young farmers, board members and trainers will be involved when suited.
g. NAJK will organize a debriefing involving the assignee, Agriterra and NAJK. This will provide a view of occurred bottlenecks and positive elements and will only improve following assignments. When appropriate ideas for a follow-up and key-persons will be identified. When a debriefing is organized by Agriterra NAJK will be invited at all times!
h. NAJK is project leader for the three year  program Support to Young Farmers of Benin in which a total of 75  young farmers will be assisted developing entrepreneurial and marketing skills. Several activities are included:
1. Dragons' Den, identification  of young farmers who can participate in the program. In the Den they present their individual  business plans to the Benin working group and Fupro .
2. Survey continuity of the program, organize and prepare activities and involve NAJK-members

Expected Results
o	Within organizations young farmers are assisted in setting up their own Young Farmers Branch
	Boards are supported and advised on the design of youth policy
o	Young boards are trained in leadership and management skills 
o	Exchanging experiences with yf organizations on how to organize and manage a farmers association
o	Assist in lobby trainings and stay involved in lobby roadmap 
	Shared knowledge on agricultural and marketing skills with 30 individual young farmers (including Benin)
o	High quality mission reports and debriefings in all cases
	Two training weekends with a maximum of 30 NAJK-members trained in intercultural communication and brainstorm methods
o	One training dedicated to Agripoolers likely to be employed again. By dealing with the specific experiences the quality of the Agripoolers services can be improved. This training is open to Agripoolers other than NAJK-members
	Social and written media used to communicate Agriterra activities to Dutch young farmers.

Young Dutch farmers support rural youth in developing countries in defending their interests, lobbying and in becoming rural entrepreneurs.

Involve more Dutch young farmers in international cooperation.

The new ovens will provide a sustainable and safe way of cooking.

title: Programme dAppui Multisectoriel à la Sécurité Alimentaire et Nutritionnelle dans lAtacora (AMSANA) : Projet "Améliorer les pratiques nutritionnelles et d'hygiène dans les communautés des villages cibles des communes de Boukoumbé, Matéri, Cobly et Tanguiéta"
description:
Lintervention (programme) AMSANA est une intervention multi-acteurs mobilisant 5 organisations partenaires (Louvain Coopération, IIes de Paix, Protos, Croix-Rouge de Belgique et l'Agence de développement belge Enabel) autour dun objectif commun de réduction de linsécurité alimentaire et nutritionnelle. Les stratégies de lutte contre linsécurité alimentaire et nutritionnelle dans la zone dintervention identifiées par lanalyse contextuelle constituent les axes principaux autour desquelles sarticulent les actions des organisations partenaires et forment les résultats du cadre logique de lintervention. Les organisations partenaires contribuent ensemble à latteinte des résultats et des objectifs de lintervention AMSANA en exécutant des composantes ou sous-composantes de lintervention (Résultats et Sous-Résultats) en fonction de leurs expertises et expérience.

Lintervention AMSANA vise à latteinte des 5 résultats suivants : 
-	Résultat 1: La sécurisation de la disponibilité des produits vivriers et maraîchers et des revenus qui en découlent
-	Résultat 2: Les populations bénéficient de services économiques adaptés pour laugmentation et la diversification de leurs revenus
-	Résultat 3: Meilleures pratiques nutritionnelles et d'hygiène dans les communautés des villages ciblés
-	Résultat 4: Les stratégies et les interventions dappui relatives à la sécurité alimentaire et à la prévention de la malnutrition sont mieux prises en charge, priorisées et exécutées aux différents niveaux institutionnels du programme
-	Résultat 5: Des effets multidimensionnels sur les ménages ciblés, l'efficience du programme et lappropriation des bonnes pratiques à tous les niveaux dintervention sont renforcés

Des stratégies destinées à renforcer légalité hommes/femmes, à protéger et améliorer lenvironnement et à atténuer limpact négatif du changement climatique ont été développées et incorporées de façon transversale dans lensemble de lintervention.

LONG Croix-Rouge de Belgique prend en charge la quasi-totalité de la composante relative à la nutrition (Résultat 3, sous-résultats 3.1, 3.2 et 3.3) à lexception du sous-résultat 3.4 qui est exécuté par lONG Protos. Projet "Améliorer les pratiques nutritionnelles et d'hygiène dans les communautés des villages cibles des communes de Boukoumbé, Matéri, Cobly et Tanguiéta" est une composante du vaste programme dappui multisectoriel à la sécurité alimentaire et nutritionnelle dans ces 4 communes (programme AMSANA) au sein duquel il prend en charge la problématique nutritionnelle qui est étroitement liée aux enjeux de sécurité alimentaire.

title: Task 16 - Confirming the axioma on the development impact of producer organisations
description:
AgriCord One-for-all: task 16

Why do agri-agencies do the work that they do? Because they think that that work (= strengthening producer organisations, farmers' unions, cooperative societies etc.) contributes to a fairer and more prosperous society. Without membership organisations that know how to promote the interests of their members, it is hard to see how fairness and democracy  can ever come into place. Alexis de Tocqueville is on our side: In order that men remain civilized or become so, the art of associating must be developed and perfected among them in the same ratio as equality of conditions increases. Besides, historically speaking, it is easy to argue that countries in Europe are, in general, pleasant to live in as a result of strong professional organisations,

This theory of change of the agri-agencies is not always accepted, sometimes even questioned. The goal of this project is to bring so much argumentation (see above) and empirical evidence together that it (the theory of change) becomes uncontested. Together with scientists, and under the coordination of Dutch research institutions and Agriterra, we wil do this in a book, to be published by October 2014: Family farms and producer organisations as generators of (rural) development.

1.	Goals

This project is to produce irrefutable evidence and publicity on the thesis of the agri-agencies that strong producer organisations have a positive influence on development, in at least three respects: economic growth, equality and democratization. The intuitive argument, the one from common sense, has never been phrased better than two centuries ago, by Alexis de Tocqueville: In order that men remain civilized or become so, the art of associating must be developed and perfected among them in the same ratio as equality of conditions increases. Historically speaking, it is easy to argue that countries in Europe are, in general, pleasant to live in as a result of strong professional organisations, preventing verticalism in decision-making and entrepreneurship. Bits and pieces of empirical evidence have also been coming forward. Its is now time to bring these intuitive and historical arguments together with real-life evidence.

2.	Proposed activities 

The task consisted and consists of the following activities:

	Dissemination of the call among relevant social scientists and practitioners, including the fellow agri-agencies (spring and summer 2013 
	Based on presentations and research activities that responded to the call, the symposium Producer organisations as generators of (rural) development was organized by CIDIN (Nijmegen), WUR (Wageningen) and Agriterra on October 10th, 2013 in Wageningen 
	Publication of a book on the topic at the occasion of the UN International Year of Family Farming (IYFF): Family farms, producer organisations and development. The book is to be edited by Roldan Muradian (CIDIN-Nijmegen), Jos Bijman (Wageningen UR) and Jur Schuurman (Agriterra). 
 
 The following time line applies for the book production: 
15 November 2013: Submission of abstracts (1 page) (see the Call, uploaded as a File under the Proposal tab)
1 December: Invitation to contribute full chapter 
Nov / Dec 2013: Editors put together synopsis of the book and negotiate with publishers 
15 January 2014: Submission of the draft contribution 
Jan + Feb 2014: Review by editors and outside reviewers 
28 February: Authors are notified about requested improvement 
30 April: Submission of final contribution 
October 2014: Book launch  

3.	Envisioned outputs and outcomes 

The main outcome is the book. It will seek to present the state of the art on socio-economic research on relationship between farmer organisations, producer organisations and other forms of economic collective action by family farmers worldwide and the impact on rural development and even development more generally. Since the World Bank published its 2008 World Development Report, producer organisations have been in the spotlight of academics and policy makers, due to renewed interest in agriculture as the main driver of rural development. Family farms are still the dominant organisational form in agricultural production, but major changes are taking place. Producer organisations have always been important for providing farmers with access to inputs and output markets. However, the increasing importance of vertical coordination in value chains and quality assurance schemes has changed the role of producer organisations and therefore their relationship with family farms. 
Producer organisations (POs) often have been associated with social capital. However, the academic debate on whether POs need to be based on existing social capital in order to function well, or whether they induce the formation of social capital, or both, is not settled. 

The book will target an audience of academics as well as practitioners interested in scientific research on the mentioned issues. It will consist of two types of contribution. About two thirds of the chapters will be academic contributions, such as literature reviews, empirical studies, conceptual papers. About one third of the book will consist of more practice-oriented chapters, such as case studies of intervention projects. It will be published by an international academic publishing house. 

Together with the experts on communication within AgriCord (and perhaps in the framework of task 15: external communication) a strategy will be devised to give due attention to the publication and its tenets, in order that the overall purpose is served: general acceptance and awareness of the thesis/axioma.  

4.	Involvement of other agri-agencies

	discussion and modification/approval of these draft TOR in Montpellier (11-12 November, 2013)
	presentation of potential contributions (abstracts) and recruitment of researchers in the respective home countries who are willing to present an abstract. UPA-DI (Canada) is actively searching for possible input. 

5.	Budget (December 2013  October 2014)

Taskmanager (Jur Schuurman): 10 days in 2013, 21 in 2014 = 31 days 
Associated task manager 1 (Kees Blokland): 5 and 10 days = 15 days 
Ass. task manager 2 (Martin Couture): 5 days 
Translations, original research, publisher's fee: 50.000

Total	EUR 95.368

6.	Proposed team leader 

Jur Schuurman, senior management advisor at Agriterra. Kees Blokland (Agriterra) and Martin Couture are involved.

7.	Justification 

With this task, AgriCord hopes to contribute to the general acceptance of the vision that development is a matter of people and their organisations. If they do not play a role in policy discussions and the realisation of concrete projects, development will never be sustainable, in the sense that there will be no ownership by the main stakeholders of development: the people who want to lift themselves out of poverty. If this vision is indeed accepted through (among others) corroboration by scientific research, the need for an elaborate impact assessment system on the work of agri-agencies will be less pressing. In other words, this project is an attempt to make the development effectiveness  of the agri-agencies' work uncontested. 

In the envisaged book, after setting forth a few more  theoretical and historical arguments, we will proceed to mention a few mechanisms that underpin this train of thought. Among them: 
	Organisations are a school for democracy instead of violence, since they make dialogue possible by their very nature 
	Organisations and associations enable joint conceptualization and policy formulation (which is always more effective than the sum of many individual formulations)
	They are a channel for uploading (from members to society as a whole) and downloading (the other way round) information, goods and services
	They enable specialisation and mobilisation of labour and capital
	They increase market power for individual farmers

to produce irrefutable evidence and publicity on the thesis of the agri-agencies that strong producer organisations have a positive influence on development, in at least three respects: economic growth, equality and democratization

title: Construction of Southern Binh Duong Solid Waste Treatment Complex Phase II
description:

title: The pink revolution Uganda
description:
Employing gender transformative contract farming as an innovative and holistic approach, this project will enhance young women farmers agency and decision-making power, while increasing their income from soy production and improving household budgeting, ultimately enhancing household resilience. 
Although smallholder farmers produce 90% of Ugandas total food output and 70% of these are women, many young women smallholder farmers in Northern Uganda (Lira, Apac, Alebtong, Dokolo and Oyam districts) do not generate sufficient income to sustain their livelihoods and provide nutritious food for themselves and their children. Gender inequality within household, community and society inhibits their access to agricultural inputs, good farming practices, market information, and affordable nutritious food. 
This project (1 April 2017  31 March 2020) combines a Women Empowerment in Agriculture approach with contract farming. The project targets the soy sector since its potential is grossly underexploited in Northern Uganda. The innovation of gender transformative contract farming lies in the incentives it creates for farmer groups to pursue gender equality within all their operations. This includes the application of bylaws on gender equality, as well as providing women with equal access to improved farming inputs, and capacity building on financial, entrepreneurial and marketing skills. 
At the end of the project, 2,500 smallholder farmers (80% young women) will be socially and economically empowered, and their livelihoods and food security will be improved beyond the project lifetime.

title: Strategic Evaluation on Communicating Research for Influence: Part I
description: IDRC aims to support research that is not just about development, or relevant to development, but that will actually influence development. In order to do so, that research has to be effectively communicated and strategically positioned. IDRC endeavours to do this is by engaging potential research users in the research process, and training research partners in communication skills (writing, publishing, presentation, etc.). IDRC is supporting an evaluation of experiences of research uptake in order to understand to what extent, where and why some research becomes influential and other research does not. This project seeks to answer the following questions. What theories underpin the influence strategies used by IDRC? Where have those theories been tried and with what results? In what contexts do those theories seem to be effective or ineffective? Does IDRC use an appropriate range of strategies compared to other research funders? The first two questions will be addressed in Part I of the project.

title: Proyecto: Fortalecimiento de las capacidades locales para la adaptación al cambio ambiental global en comunidades rurales e indígenas mexicanas
description: México alberga una gran biodiversidad y una elevada riqueza cultural, concentrada en la región sudeste del país, donde se plantea este proyecto. Específicamente, se pretende trabajar con dos poblaciones ubicadas en la Reserva de la Biosfera de Calakmul, caracterizadas por ser comunidades migrantes de indígenas y mestizos campesinos, cuyas prácticas de manejo se están viendo afectadas tanto por factores políticos, socio-económicos y climáticos. Con este proyecto, se pretende: 1) reforzar las capacidades locales en el uso de herramientas útiles y replicables para monitoreo socio-ecológico que les permitan detectar, observar y plantear acciones para lidiar con los cambios socio-ecológicos que pueden afectar a sus medios de vida, 2) generar espacios de diálogo, reflexión y construcción de conocimiento sobre escenarios de futuro que fortalezcan la participación comunitaria en la toma de decisiones sobre la gestión de sus recursos naturales y, 3) difundir el conocimiento mediante la elaboración participativa de material educativo y de divulgación reforzando la colaboración inter-universitaria (INECOL-UAB) y con las comunidades locales
UNIV UAB - Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona

title: Frame Agreement with NGO (Finn Church Aid)
description:
HIV/AIDS implications on the Mozambican communities are dire. For example, it has led to a reduction of life expectancy at birth and consequently to the reduction of the HDI. At present, 15% of pregnant women between 15-49 years are HIV positive. Demograph
ic impact of AIDS for 2008 estimate that in 2009, nearly 1.6 million people were living with HIV/AIDS. These included 55.5% women + 9.2% children younger than 15 years. The project aims at supporting communities to reduce risk and vulnerability to HIV infe
ction and to alleviate the impact of the epidemic on the affected households with a strong focus on women, through development of the economic capacities of the most vulnerable households and promotion of human rights, particularly the rights of PLWHAs (Pe
ople Living with HIV/AIDS) and OVCs (Orphaned and Vulnerable Children) in the urban districts of Kamatova and Kamaxaquene. These are high density suburbs located in the outskirts of Maputo City in Mozambique. The area has high poverty rates and prone to pa
ndemic diseases such as cholera, malaria and HIV/AIDS. In addition, the area is one of the central when it comes to domestic violence and other human rights violations, prostitution, and sexual abuse against women and young girls due to poverty.Objectives:
1. Improved food security2. Improved knowledge on pandemics at household level3. Strengthened capacities of Community Based Organisations4. Increased access of communities to Credit 5. Increased capacity of staff in implementing the  project Activities: a.
 Promoting home gardeningb. Promoting income generationc. Facilitating and supporting  savings and credit schemesd. Promoting access to education for vulnerable childrene. Promoting vocational training for vulnerable youth f. Supporting  community based gr
oups and organisationsg. Raising awareness on  harmfulness of domestic violenceh. Home-based care to HIV-patients and psycho-social support to HIV-affected familiesThe main right-holders /beneficiaries of the project are 1500 vulnerable households from the
 urban districts of Kamavota and Kamaxaquene in Maputo City. These are vulnerable households from mainly women headed households, OVCs, Elderly and handicapped people. The project aims to reach at least 60% women beneficiaries. The project reaches also Dev
elopment Committee Members in each of the 6 villages, Peer Educators, members of HIV Associations and activists from the selected areas, and locals school students.Implementing partner: The Ecumen
Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland

title: Building safer and more resilient communities in central Region and strengthen national system for disaster risk reduction in Mozambique
description: This intervention aims to increase the resilience of communities in the low Licungo and Zambezi river basins enhancing early warning information (through EWS) working with other organizations to jointly produce a more complex program at the national level. Regarding the EWS, incorporating new communities in the flow system, with the capacitation of 4 new District Technical Councils (Morrumbala, Ile and Gurue in Zambezia Province; Chemba in Sofala Province). These districts and councils differ from the trained under HIP 2016 (Maganja da Costa, Namacurra, Mutarara and Caia). Local Disaster Risk Management Committees strategy would be based on offering tailor made improvements, supporting INGC to implement sustainability solutions, and providing training in first aid to key members of the LDRMC. 31 new communities along the basins will be included in data winners in HIP 2017 so communities targeted under HIP 2016 will not be included under HIP 2017. If due to the comprehensive approach of this new intervention some overlapping exists, the components of the actions implemented will be different (avoiding double funding).Intervention includes also activities at institutional level, reinforcing the District Comissions of the Red Cross in terms of means and training, as well as at the national level, in specific areas such as Cash Transfer. Specific advocacy interventions are proposed, such as recognition of first aid into INGC curriculum, Cash Transfer and Social Protection advocacy and achieving final recognition of host families in emergency dislocation.HIP 2016: provinces of Tete (Mutarara district), Sofala (Caia), Manica (Manica) and Zambezia (Maganja da Costa and Namacurra). HIP 2017: Provinces of Sofala (Caia and Chemba) and Zambezia (Maganja da Costa, Namacurra, Mopeia, Morrumbala, Ille, Gurue and Chinde). HIP 2017 aims to achieve a greater coverage area, targeting new districts through different strategies.

title: Fortalecimiento de la organización y de las capacidades productivas de las asociaciones de mujeres en comunidades rurales. Fase II
description: "Fortalecimiento de la organización y de las capacidades productivas de las asociaciones de mujeres en comunidades rurales. Fase II :: El proyecto pretende potenciar la organización de mujeres en dos comunidades rurales de la comune de Djedougou en Malí. Al mismo tiempo fortalecer las capacidades productivas en torno a dos ejes estratégicos: Un primer eje a través de talleres de formación para mujeres sobre los aspectos fundamentales de la organización, legalización y gestión de asociaciones de mujeres, y Un segundo eje está vinculado con la producción de alimentos y la mejora de los cultivos a través de la rehabilitación de dos huertos comunitarios de mujeres pertenecientes a estas asociaciones con el objetivo de generar ingresos que mejoren la autonomía y la autoestima de las mujeres asociadas El proyecto se desarrollará en tres fases; una primera fase de socialización, organización y elaboración del POA, una segunda fase consistirá en las labores de construcción de pozos para riego, cerramiento de los jardins de femmes ? huertos comunitarios de mujeres, construcción de los centros de reunión y almacenaje y la puesta en marcha de la producción, y una tercera fase, paralela a la anterior será la realización de ciclos formativos, mediante metodología participativa, pero adaptada al nivel académico de las socias. Con esto se espera que las asociaciones de mujeres tengan capacidad para mejorar su organización, mejorar sus ingresos y favorecer el acceso a alimentos básicos para sus familias. "

title: Bangladesh - Employment Generation Program for the Poorest
description: The objective of the Employment Generation Program for the Poorest Project (EGPP) for Bangladesh is to provide the short-term employment on community sub-projects to enable households to better cope with vulnerability, while strengthening program implementation. There are two components to the components to the project. The project follows a results-based financing mechanism and disbursement-linked indicators (DLIs) representing targets to trigger disbursement are specified for each year of implementation of the Government program of the same name. One DLI focus area pertains to the use of a specific geographic targeting formula to allocate fiscal resources to ensure pro-poor coverage. The DLI target for 2013, for this focus area, will need to be changed as the follow-on Safety Net Systems for the Poorest (SNSP) Project, which will commence implementation and support the same Government program during the same year, includes an updated geographic targeting formula based on new national poverty statistics. It was agreed during negotiations for the SNSP Project that the new DLI targets agreed for the Government program will apply to the EGPP Project, thereby necessitating an amendment to the EGPP project's financing agreement. This will constitute a level two restructuring. The changes will amend the DLI target for geographic targeting in 2013 to ensure that the provisions under the EGPP Financing Agreement, and the recently signed SNSP financing agreement, are aligned.
MINISTRY OF FOOD AND DISASTER MGT

reporting.org: Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland
title: Sustainable Forest Use and Food Security
description:
Forest resources are used unsustainably in and around Kiwengwa-Pongwe Forest Reserve because of poor farming techniques lack of available land and limited livelihood opportunities in the 12 villages surrounding it. For the same reasons the communities also
 suffer from food insecurity which threatens their right to adequate food. Project aims to tackle these development problems by enhancing sustainable forest management including both conservation and sound usage of forest resources and improving food secur
ity of these communities. To achieve its objectives the project supports agroforestry and other livelihoods such as sea shell and sea weed farming and livestock and beekeeping by providing training and initial material support to groups of community member
s hoping to develop their livelihoods. It also supports tree planting establishes tree nurseries in the area builds wood fuel saving stoves raises environmental awareness and provides capacity building to community based forestry actors.The development pol
icy objectives of gender equality and reduction of inequality are met by supporting livelihood groups of women and agricultural production in which women have an important role and by improving the availability of stable food crops crucial to the most vuln
erable members in the communities. Integrating trees into farming systems planting trees promoting improved stoves and livelihoods relying on forest well-being will conserve biodiversity and biomass in the area so as to combat climate change. While diversi
fying local people's livelihoods will help the communties to adapt to the effects of climate change.The direct beneficiaries of the project are the 26 supported groups engaging in their livelihood initiatives 200 households receiving wood fuel saving stove
s 11 Forest Conservation Committees (FCCs) and the local partner DFNR. In the end the project benefits the entire village communities of approximately 28 000 inhabitants by improving the access and availability of food in their villages. The project is mai
nly working with the existing structures of and between DFNR FCCs and the village communities but it also supports the activities of newly established umbrella organization of FCCs called Kiwengwa-Pongwe Community Forest Conservation Network (K-P CFCN). K-
P CFCN will receive capacity training during the project for it to fully function as a community based organization enhancing local level forest management in the future.
Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland
Finnish NGO, Geographical Society of Turku

title: OECD investment (PFI update) technical assistance
description:
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) approved its Policy Framework for Investment in 2006. OECD ministers agreed to use the PFI as part of their development cooperation. The objective of this project is to update the PFI tool so tha
t it can be better applied to the challenges of sustainable development. The aim is to have a wide participation to the update by OECD non-member countries (especially developing countries) and non-state actors such as civil society organizations. In the u
pdate process will be discussed topics such as environment gender equality agriculture infrastructure updated OECD guidelines for multinational enterprises as well as the UN guiding principles on business and human rights. The objective of the project is t
o help developing countries benefit from sustainable investment. Beneficiaries of the project are developing countries' societies in large i.e. firms non-state actors workers government.

Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development

title: Youth Alive Zambia: CHOOSE LIFE Project
description:
Zambias Gender Inequality Index (GII) in 2012 stood at 0.623, ranking it 136 out of 148 countries. Compared to a slight improvement in 2015. According to the World Economic Forum's Global Gender Gap Index for 2015, Zambia is ranked 116, out of 145 countries. This means that Zambia is rated among the worst 30 countries with the highest levels of gender inequality in the whole world. Zambia is also ranked third highest country with cases of child marriages in the SADC region, according to Girls Not Brides, with 42% of women aged 20-24 years married by the age of 18, many of whom live in rural areas among the poor and marginalized communities. Approximately 25.7% of adult women have reached a secondary or higher level of education compared to 44.2% of their male counterparts. Gender inequality is a key determinant of risky behaviour in sexual relationships. In addition, gender inequality contributes to hinder womens access to adequate information, education and services on health. This project will stimulate the debate among children and youths concerning gender relations in their own schools, communities and jointly reflect on possible measures to overcome the negative effects of gender inequality. Public events in the covered communities will address the issues of gender as well as of child and youth policies in the context of gender. This action will promote an open dialogue among children, youths and parents on these issues. As girls do not drop out from school due to early marriage, the number of girls attaining basic or higher education is expected to increase, which in turn contributes to more informed choices about teenage pregnancy. Parents are expected to assume more responsibility for the future of their girls and change socio-cultural patterns that expose them to risks of particularly dropping out of school, early or forced marriages. Project outcomes:
1. Increased girls and young peoples (aged 10 to 24 years) access to and retention in education reduces their vulnerability to contracting HIV.
2. Reduced adolescent girls and young womens (aged 10  24 years) vulnerability to unintended pregnancy and Sexual Gender Based Violence. 
3. Improved livelihood skills of out of school young people aged 19 to 24 years for an effective response to poverty and HIV.
4. Improved knowledge on gender equality among young people (15-24 years), for an effective response to gender inequality and HIV.
5. Improved capacity for system and project management of YAZ

title: Agricultural Productivity Program for Southern Africa - Angola & Lesotho
description: The development objective of the Agricultural Productivity Program (APP) Project for Angola, Lesotho, and Center for Coordination of Agricultural Research and Development for Southern Africa is to increase the availability of improved agricultural technologies in participating countries in the Southern Africa Development Community (SADC) region. The project comprises of four components. The first component, technology generation and dissemination will finance innovative research and development (R and D) technology generation and dissemination activities associated with the commodity groups or technology themes being targeted by countries participating in APP Southern Africa (SA). The second component, strengthening the institutional and enabling environment for technology adoption will finance: (i) upgrading of research infrastructure including rehabilitation and construction of on-farm infrastructure, the estacao experimental agricola (agricultural research stations) (EEAs) and campo experimental agricola (agricultural research fields) (CEAs) research laboratory, and research and office equipment; and information technology and knowledge management systems; (ii) upgrading of infrastructure for sanitary and phytosanitary (SPS) management and regulatory systems; (iii) improving institutional administration and performance management systems within regional center of leadership (RCoLs); (iv) developing human capital, with special focus on promoting women scientists, by providing scientific or technical training at the post graduate level and by upgrading skills through short courses or targeted training, and scientific exchanges; (v) strengthening seed production capacity, seed regulatory functions, and related services, and (vi) improving national research regulatory system to facilitate national agricultural research system (NARS) functionality and implementation of

title: Growth and Economic Opportunities for Women: Research Call Activities
description:
The Growth and Economic Opportunities for Women (GrOW) research program is a joint initiative of IDRC, the United Kingdom Department for International Development, and The William and Flora Hewlett Foundation. It represents a joint investment of CA$16.4 million over five years. This project will provide funding to support the program's objectives through a competitive call for proposals and selection of projects.

GrOW aims to address knowledge gaps on women's economic empowerment and the connections with economic growth. It also strives to stimulate innovative research partnerships and engagement with policymakers. This funding will help the GrOW team select 15 to 20 projects by covering capacity-building costs related to the research call and project selection process.
Great Britain. Dept for International Development

title: Beschäftigungsintensives Investitionsprogramm für Jordanier und syrische Flüchtlinge in Jordanien
description: Das Ziel der FZ-Maßnahme ist die kurzfristige Schaffung von Beschäftigung für syrische Flüchtlinge und Jordanier sowie ein mittelfristig erleichterter Zugang zum Arbeitsmarkt für die Zielgruppe. Im Mittelpunkt des Vorhabens stehen schnell anlaufende arbeitsintensive Infrastrukturmaßnahmen wie Straßenrehabilitierung, Zisternenbau und Schulerweiterungen. Diese werden begleitet durch Schulungsmaßnahmen in arbeitsintensivem Bau, Unterstützung des Arbeitsministeriums zur Ausstellung von Arbeitsgenehmigungen für syrische Flüchtlinge sowie berufsqualifizierende Kurzausbildungen (on-the-job trainings). Die Maßnahmen werden vor allem in den nördlichen Gouvernoraten Mafraq und Irbid durchgeführt, die einen hohen Anteil syrischer Flüchtlinge beherbergen. Zielgruppe sind syrische Flüchtlinge (männlich und weiblich) und jordanische Männer und Frauen, die von der Krise in Mafraq und Irbid betroffen sind.
Bundesministerium für wirtschaftliche Zusammenarbeit und Entwicklung (BMZ)

title: Promotion of sexual and reproductive health and rights and education of girls in rural Malawi
description:
The project is implemented by Vaestoliitto Mannerheim League for Child Welfare (MLL) Youth Empowerment and Civic Education Family Planning Association of Malawi and College of Medicine University of Malawi. Its activities are in the Republic of Malawi in D
edza and Mangochi districts in 6 schools. There is a high school drop-out among girls aged 10-18 which is as a result of unfriendly school environment unsupportive community environment lack of empowerment of girls and poor sexual health. Reasons for drop-
outs are e.g. sexual harassment early marriages and pregnancies family responsibilities and long distances. The aim of the project is to develop capacity of the partners develop models and strengthen the already existing structures in the project area. Fur
thermore the aim is to improve the implementation of the national policies within youth and girls sexual and reproductive health and rights and education on the local level especially in the project area. The specific objectives are, 1) CSO capacity buildi
ng 2) Girl friendly and safer schools in project area 3) Supportive community environment for girls? education and sexual and reproductive health and rights in project area 4) Girls are empowered in the project area.The outputs are: 1) Comprehensive approa
ch by partners in development of well-being and health of girls in the project area 2) Model of SRHR friendly school is established 3) Model of safe school environment is established 4) Community members promote actively education and well-being of girls i
n the project area 5) Girls have responsible role in project implementation. The development objective is to contribute to the improvement of well-being and health of Malawian girls. The Finnish cross-cutting goals are taken into consideration in monitorin
g and evaluation. The focus is on human rights and gender equality. The project focuses on training key groups in communities on project themes develops models for schools on safe and supportive environment and sexual education conducts research analyses c
ollected data and strengthens existing structures. In the implementation such models are adopted as Integrated Area Based Approach peer support and school peace of MLL and Steps of Sexuality -sexuality education of Vaestoliitto. The beneficiaries on the pr
oject area are girls aged 10-18 years teachers boys community leaders and parents. Project sustainability is secured a.o. by working with existing structures.
Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland
University of Malawi College of Medicine Centre for Reproductive Health

title: WFP HUM 2015-2018
description:
Sidas humanitära enhet genomför årligen en global allokeringsprocess där samtliga pågående humanitära kriser analyseras utifrån humanitära behov. Humanitära samarbetspartners förmåga att svara mot dessa behov bedöms i respektive kontext, varefter Sida föreslår lämplig fördelning av tillgängliga humanitära medel till respektive land och partner. I början på 2018 rapporterade FN att 135 miljoner människor i 26 länder är i behov av humanitär hjälp. Flertalet av dessa människor är drabbade av matosäkerhetskriser, såsom i Somalia, Jemen, Nigeria, Sydsudan och Sudan.

Det nu föreslagna stödet avser ny finansiering till FN:s världslivsmedelsprogram (WFP) för stöd till humanitära insatser under 2018 och uppgår till sammanlagt 146,5 MSEK. Insatserna är fördelade mellan främst livsmedelsdistribution och transport i sammanlagt 11 länder.

WFP, grundad 1961, är en av världens största humanitära organisationer med närvaro i 80 länder och 14,000 anställda. WFP:s primära mål är att, genom livsmedelsbistånd, rädda liv och säkra försörjningsförmåga i kris- och katastrofsituationer. WFP är en mycket relevant organisation för det humanitära arbetet, då de har hög kapacitet inom logistik och förmåga att snabbt etablera sig i fält, även i högriskområden. Utöver att rädda liv genom matdistribution, bidrar WFP:s insatser till att upprätthålla människors värdighet genom bl.a. utdelning av kontanter som ökar människors självförsörjning. WFP arbetar för minskad global hunger vilket i sin tur förbättrar människors möjlighet att tillvarata sina mänskliga rättigheter. Över 90% av hela WFP:s personalstyrka arbetar på plats i länderna.

På senare år har WFP:s kontantbaserade insatser ökat markant där målgrupperna mottar pengar (elektroniskt, kontant eller via checkar), i stället för fysisk distribution av livsmedel. Detta har medfört mer kostnadseffektiva och flexibla insatser, i de kriser där fungerande marknader finns att tillgå. Genom att tillämpa landprogram påvisar WFP en djup förståelse för kopplingen mellan humanitärt bistånd och utvecklingssamarbete. Landprogrammen består av strategiska mål och fokusområden som behandlar grundorsaker, resiliens och krisrespons.

Sida har ett omfattande humanitärt samarbete med WFP sedan många år tillbaka. Organisationen mottar årligen både riktat humanitärt landstöd från Sida, såväl som s.k. kärnstöd från UD.

MATSTÖD OCH STÄRKT MOTSTÅNDSKRAFT
Av 2018 års stöd från Sida, totalt 146,5 MSEK avses 93,5 MSEK att används för akuta matsäkerhetsinsatser i form av:
1) Distribution av livsmedel till utsatta familjer, exempelvis ris, majs, matolja och socker.
2) Kontantbaserat stöd (vouchers och elektroniska kort) för inköp av livsmedel på lokala marknader.
3) Behandlande och förebyggande nutritionsinsatser, exempelvis genom distribution av särskilt vitamin- och proteinberikad kost till undernärda barn.

Stödet till akuta matsäkerhetsinsatser föreslås till följande kriser: 
1) Demokratiska folkrepubliken Korea (Nordkorea) 11 MSEK
2) Etiopien 25 MSEK 
3) Demokratiska republiken Kongo (DRK) 22,5 MSEK
4) Somalia 25 MSEK
5) Sudan 10 MSEK

UNHAS OCH LOGISTIK
På grund av exempelvis långa avstånd, pågående stridigheter eller bristfälliga vägar är många människor utom räckhåll för insatser. Därför föreslås att resterande stöd på 49 MSEK att användas till finansiering av United Nations Humanitarian Air Services (UNHAS), för att förbättra tillträde till människor i behov av humanitär hjälp. UNHAS transporterar även hjälporganisationers personal och bidrar till ökad säkerhet under arbete i fält.

Transportstödet riktas till följande kontexter: 1) Centralafrikanska republiken (CAR) 8 MSEK, 2) Tchad 5 MSEK, 3) Demokratiska republiken Kongo (DRK) 10 MSEK, 4) Kamerun 3 MSEK, 5) Mali 4 MSEK, 6) Niger 5 MSEK, 7) Nigeria 9 MSEK och 8) Sudan 5 MSEK.

Utöver ovanstående föreslås även 4 MSEK fördelas till Emergency Telecommunications Cluster (ETC) i Nigeria. En begränsad del av stödet kommer att användas för insatser

title: F.a: Refugees in Nyanza Lac in Burundi
description:
Thousands of Burundian refugees are sent back to their homeland every year from the neighbouring countries. The project helps refugees in Nyanza Lac in Burundi to reintegrate in the country. They are offered help to build their own house and they are also 
given agricultural tools, seeds and mosquito nets. So far 270 households have benefitted from this help. A health station, which the returning refugees can benefit from, is getting equipped and renovated through the project. Sewing courses are arranged for
 young women who otherwise would have difficulties supporting themselves. When they finish the course they are given a sewing machine and can start earning money by sewing clothes. The project is supported in cooperation with Community of Pentecostal Churc
hes in Burundin (CEPBU). CEPBU has long experience of humanitarian aid and development projects.

title: Project for Indonesian Tax Administration Reform (PINTAR)
description: The Tax Administration Reform Project (PINTAR) for Indonesia aims to: a) increase taxpayer compliance by increasing the efficiency and effectiveness of the Directorate General of Tax (DGT); and b) improve good governance in tax administration by strengthening transparency and accountability mechanisms. There are four components to the project. The first component of the project is increasing the efficiency of taxpayer data collection and management. This component aims at improving taxpayer registration, returns processing, taxpayer accounts management, documents management, and Information and Communications Technology (ICT) infrastructure. The second component of the project is human resource management and development. This component will support and strengthen ongoing reforms in DGT by addressing basic capacity building needs related to the main functions and improving training capacity. It will also support the improvement of human resource policies and strengthen anti-corruption policies and mechanisms. The third component of the project is strengthening compliance management operations. This component will increase the efficiency of selected core operational functions of tax administration. It will concentrate on: a) tax audit, introducing risk-based audit selection, reforming business processes for desk and field audit, computerizing processes supporting the tax audit function, and improving the audit planning and monitoring process; and b) arrears collection, in particular enhancing the arrears monitoring system, reforming business processes for arrears collection, and enhancing the collection enforcement ICT system. The fourth and final component of the project is project and change management. title: ICCO-El Nino II
description:
Based on the priorities set in Zimbabwe 2016/2017, the primary focus of this intervention is premised under Food Security <(>&<)> Agriculture to provide food assistance through unconditional cash transfer to selected most vulnerable households while at the same time building coommunity capacity to restore lost productive assets at the household level.  The action builds on achievements made during the first phase of  ZIM JR. It aims at saving the lives of of 10,780 drought affected persons in Mwenezi, Lupane and Chivi districts. The unconditional cash transfer will remain the preferred model of food assistance being informed  by ongoing market assessments in the selected areas.  The programme recognises the  need for continuous monitoring of the cash crises persisting in the country despite the recent introduction of bond notes.
I<(>&<)>K/ACT will collaborate with Terre des Hommes in strengthening the ISAL and agricultural component through inclusive finance trainings to beneficiaries of cash transfers in order to promote savings, investment in agricultural assets and income generating activities that increase diversity of income sources for households. Lessons learntand challenges will be shared with other ZIMJR-2 partners at national level.

In 2016-2021, the Joint Programme will support a One United Nations, working closely with Cosponsors, maximizing comparative advantages at country level in relation to other development partners, and supporting national efforts to Fast-Track the AIDS response towards ending the AIDS epidemic as a public health threat by 2030. The Secretariat will broker, strengthen and leverage synergy and accountability between technical support mechanisms and providers of essential HIV services

title: International Institute for Water and Environmental Engineering (2ie)
description: The objective of the International Institute for Water and Environmental Engineering (2iE) Project for Burkina Faso is to increase the number of highly skilled professionals in the areas of water, energy, environment, and infrastructure engineering which are vital fields for Africa's development. It will do so by supporting the development of 2iE as a regional center of excellence, in particular by: (i) further increasing the capacity of the 2iE campuses in Kamboinse and Ouagadougou to train and board students; (ii) improving the quality of training and research programs, particularly at master and doctorate levels; and (iii) improving the institute's management and communication capacity. There are three components to the project. The first component of the project will increase the capacity of 2iE from 520 students to 1000 students by: (i) expanding the overall infrastructure of the 2iE campuses, including boarding facilities and student life facilities; (ii) improving the pedagogic and research capacity with a main scientific building hosting research laboratories, researchers offices and experimentation facilities, two adjustable pedagogic halls (500 and 400 seats), a conference hall (250 seats) and classroom facilities; and (iii) rehabilitating existing infrastructure in the two campuses, in particular for electrical and fire safety. The second component of the project will improve the quality of training and research by: (i) equipping world class scientific laboratories in key areas: pollution control and water treatment in tropical environment, water and irrigation in Sub-Saharan environment, biomass energy and bio-fuel, interdisciplinary mathematics modeling, environment and eco-health and building eco-materials, and improving language learning and developing e-learning; and (ii) developing postgraduate diplomas and strengthening the capacity of teaching staff
INTERNATIONAL INSTITUTE FOR WATER & ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEERIN

title: ANBTI - Merapu Indigenous - ID
description:
Merapu Indigenous communities in West Sumba, East Nusa Tenggara is still facing the discrimination and exclusion in many aspects oftheir livelihoods. This exclusion results in their prevalent poverty, inaccessibility of proper education, their low rate of socio-political participation, particularly as a rightful citizen.

Following the situation, Bhinneka Tunggal Ika Alliance (ANBTI) initiates an empowerment project with Marapu communities using participatory action strategy, which works closely with the involved communities. This approach enables the indigenous people to identify the key issues that they face and struggle, and to formulate appropriate action plans and advocation that are suitable for their condition. Organizing the communities has been the key to conduct the participatory action. By organizing, we would like to form a new community working as facilitator to implement the actions within theother communities. Through organizing as well, we are also capable of pinpointing potentials that are held by the communities and how to develop those potentials according to their needs. The involvement of local capacities and potentials is really crucial to maintain the sustainability of the program.

Organizing the communities also means to build a platform for the people to do many activities together with their members. Thus, it is necessary for the communities to build a communal space for collective gathering, discussions, and capacity development. We would like to establish Community-Based Learning Center. This new learning space for community is intended to be the starting point for driving changes in the community. A strong foundation of livelihoods enables the societyto effectively and significantly participate in the state as its rightful members, including to self-advocate their rights and needs, particularly regarding the administration and civil rights. Through this platform, the communities will run the program that is planned and constructed rogether to advocate their rights.

title: Diakonia rambidrag 2015
description:
Diakonia ansöker om rambidrag för 2015 från anslaget för stöd genom svenska organisationer i det civila samhället om 160 miljoner SEK.

Ansökande organisation:
Diakonia är en biståndsorganisation med kristna värderingar, vars huvudmän är frikyrkorna Svenska Alliansmissionen och Equmeniakyrkan. Diakonia har haft ramavtal med Sida sedan tidigt 1990-tal. Statusen som ramorganisation förnyades i början av 2014, efter att en ramkriteriebedömning genomförts. Diakonia har fyra regionkontor och 24 landkontor i Afrika, Asien, Latinamerika och Mellanöstern. 

Ansökan:
Ansökan utgör en förlängning av pågående ramprogram 2012-2014. Ansökan är inte komplett i sig själv, utan presenterar endast förändringar i förhållande till pågående program. Uppgifter som saknades i ansökan har Sida begärt in i efterhand från Diakonia. Bl.a. gäller det ett uppdaterat resultatramverk, en kostnadseffektivitetsanalys, en motivering av höjningen av budgeten samt en uppdaterad insatslista. Budgeten är inte korrekt uppställd, då indelningen av budgeten i verksamhetskostnader hos Diakonia respektive hos lokala samarbetsparter inte följer Sidas riktlinjer.

Ansökan omfattar 20 landprogram i Afrika, Asien, Latinamerika och Mellanöstern samt två regionala program i Afrika. Verksamheten är inriktad på fem tematiska områden: mänskliga rättigheter, demokrati, jämställdhet, social och ekonomisk rättvisa samt fred och försoning. Diakonia arbetar genom lokala samarbetsorganisationer. Totalt 233 ingår i denna ansökan. Kapacitetsutveckling av dessa utgör en viktig del av insatsen.

Diakonias övergripande mål är att förändra de politiska, ekonomiska, sociala och kulturella strukturer som skapar fattigdom, förtryck och våld. Diakonia stöder en bred krets av civila samhällesorganisationer med utgångspunkt från sin förändringsteori som fokuserar på medvetenhet och kunskap om rättigheter, mobilisering samt kollektivt agerande och påverkansarbete.

Förväntade resultat:
Förväntade resultat specificeras per land/regionalt program. Det är stora skillnader mellan programmen i hur resultaten utformas. Sida bedömer att de förväntade resultaten i flera fall är på en väl övergripande nivå, men de indikatorer som anges konkretiserar dem och gör dem uppföljningsbara. Exempel på förväntade resultat, ett från varje region, inom några vanliga tematiska områden är:
"Kenya: Förbättrad tillgång till rättslig prövning för rättighetsbärarna."
"Peru: Andinska lantbrukarorganistioner och urfolksorganisationer i Amazonas genomdriver sina kollektiva rättigheter för hållbart nyttjande av naturresurser och för att minska sårbarheten vad gälller klimatförändringar, på ett jämställt, rättighetsbaserat och interkulturellt sätt, genom att utveckla sin kapacitet för påverkansarbete och för att skapa och genomföra alternativa förslag."
"Bangladesh: Jämställdhet har stärkts och fördomar relaterade till kön har minskat".
"Libanon: Diakonias partners har stärkt sin organisationskapacitet och tematiska kunskap." 

Tidigare resultatuppfyllelse:
Sidas bedömning, baserat på tidigare erfarenhet och ramkriteriebedömningen är att Diakonia har god förmåga att uppnå resultaten. Resultatrapporteringen pekar ofta på resultat i termer av att rättighetsbärare har blivit stärkta och kapacitet hos samarbetsorganisationer har ökat. Exempel på tidigare resultat inom ett par områden:
- Demokrati: I Burkina Faso har samarbetspartners arbetat med att demokratisera gruvindustrin bl.a. genom kompetensutveckling och informationskampanjer. Det finns nu ett starkt engagemang för att eliminera barnarbete i gruvorna.
- Jämställdhet: Kvinnoorganisationer i Bolivia, Peru och Colombia har utvecklat elva förslag på lagar och policys för att skydda kvinnors rättigheter. Förslagen berör områden som kvinnors rätt till land, trakasserier och politiskt våld mot kvinnor, trafficking och kvinnors deltagande vid fredsförhandlingar.

title: Familienplanung und HIV-AIDS-Prävention IV
description: Das FZ-finanzierte Serienvorhaben wird seit 2003 im Niger durchgeführt. Es befindet sich derzeit in der vierten Phase (BMZ-Nr. 2011 65 729). Die fünfte Phase wurde als Vorratsprüfung bereits geprüft. Die Unterzeichnung des Finanzierungsvertrags der Phase V ist für 2013 vorgesehen. Mit durchschnittlich fast 8 Geburten pro Frau, sowie einem hohen Vorkommen an schwangerschaftsbedingten Komplikationen ist Familienplanung ein zentrales Thema für die nigrische Gesundheitspolitik. Trotz einer stabilen HlV-Prävalenz von 0,7% ist das Risiko der Ausbreitung der Epidemie insbesondere in dicht besiedelten Gebieten und in den Grenzgebieten im Süden, sowie bei Menschen mit erhöhtem Infektionsrisiko (Prostituier-te, Fernfahrer) deutlich höher (ca. 36%). Das übergeordnete entwicklungspolitische Ziel der FZ-Maßnahme ist die Verbesserung der sexuellen und reproduktiven Gesundheit und Rech-te der nigrischen Bevölkerung durch die Verringerung von sexuell übertragbaren Infektionen, insbesondere HIV, die Vermeidung ungeplanter Schwangerschaften und die Vergrößerung der Geburtenabstände. Das Programm richtet sich mit der HIV-Komponente an Zielgruppen wie Fernfahrer und Prostituierte, aber auch an die allgemeine Bevölkerung im reproduktiven Alter. Die Social Marketing Agentur (SMA) ANIMAS-Sutura hat sich als dynamische und umsetzungsstarke Durchführungsstruktur etabliert und vermarktet mittlerweile neben Kondomen und der Pille auch Wasserreinigungstabletten. Im August 2012 begannen die Aktivitäten der Phase IV (5 Mio. EUR). Die vorratsgeprüfte Phase V sieht ebenfalls 5 Mio. EUR vor. In der Phase IV und V sind die weitere Stärkung der SMA, die Ausweitung der erfolgreichen Kommunikationskampagnen, die u.a. auch verstärkt Männer und ältere Schulkinder ansprechen sollen, und die Einführung eines neuen Produktes geplant.
Bundesministerium für wirtschaftliche Zusammenarbeit und Entwicklung (BMZ)
