title: Nationell Expert Tanzania Strategy Planning HRBA
description:
Europeiska unionens delegation till Tanzania och den östafrikanska gemenskapen är en nyckelaktör i förbindelserna mellan Europeiska unionen och Tanzania samt den östafrikanska gemenskapen. I nära samordning med EU-medlemsstaternas ambassader är dess roll att:
 dela den Europeiska unionens värderingar och intressen
 främja grundläggande rättigheter, gott styre och ansvarig demokrati
 stödja Tanzanias utvecklingsagenda och hållbara utvecklingsmål för ett bättre liv för alla
 stimulera inkluderande tillväxt, privat sektor och skapande av arbetstillfällen
 främja regional fred och stabilitet, ekonomisk integration och handelsutveckling

Under den direkta ledningen av biståndschefen på EU-delegationen kommer den nationella experten att stödja delegationens arbete i att stärka strategisk planering och resultatstyrning. Detta omfattar att främja en strategi för mänskliga rättigheter (HRBA) i EU:s utvecklingssamarbete, med tonvikt på jämställdhet och kvinnors egenmakt. Uppdraget kommer att innehålla fokus på fördjupning av fattigdoms- och maktanalys samt EU-gemensam programmering. Tanzania är såväl för EU-kommisisonen som Sverige ett av de största samarbetsländerna i Afrika och tjänsten erbjuder en möjlighet att effektivisera samarbetet samt förbättra svensk kunskap om den operativa biståndsverksamheten på en EU-delegation. 

Sammanlagt inkom två ansökningar, bägge beömdes uppfylla kraven i arbetsbeskrivningen. EU-delegationen i Dar es Salaam ansvarade för den slutliga bedömningen av kandidaterna och har efter bedömning och intervju valt slutkandidat för tjänsten.

title: Global Innovation Fund
description:
Global Innovation Fund (GIF) syftar till att facilitera framväxten av innovationer som löser utvecklingsproblem på ett mer effektivt sätt än de lösningar som finns tillgängliga idag. Med innovationer menas nya affärsmodeller, policies, teknologier, beteenden eller sätt att leverera produkter eller tjänster som gynnar människor som lever i fattigdom i utvecklingsländer. GIF vill bidra till storskaliga lösningar som ger miljontals människor möjligheten att öka sin livskvalité. 

För att åstadkomma detta har GIF ett flexibelt angreppssätt som skiljer sig från många andra fonder. GIF är öppen för alla typer av innovatörer (civilsamhällesaktörer, privata sektorn, myndigheter, akademin etc) inom alla sektorer. Finansieringen anpassas efter innovatörernas respektive behov och sträcker sig från ett par hundratusen till drygt hundra miljoner kronor i formen av gåvor, lån och/eller investeringar (equity). GIF har inga fönster eller ansökningsperioder utan är ständigt öppen för ansökningar. Syftet med detta flexibla upplägg är att säkerställa att inga innovationer faller mellan stolarna på grund av tematiskt eller geografiskt fokus, men också att öka konkurrensen för att få fram de bästa idéerna. 

GIF har en rigorös ansökningsprocess som beståd av flera olika steg, där innovationerna granskas inom fyra områden: Innovation and Impact, Potential to Scale, Measuring Success and Sharing Lessons Learned samt Team. Utöver detta görs "due dilligence" med fokus på t.ex. miljöfrågor, organisations- och finansiell kapacitet samt intern styrning och kontroll. En ansökan till GIF består av en kortfattad beskrivning av innovationen (t.ex. i text, video eller annat format), vilken granskas enligt ovan kriterier. De mest givande innovationerna ombeds skicka in en full ansökan. Därefter görs två av varandra oberoende granskningar av externa aktörer med relevant geografisk och tematisk expertis, som väljer ut ett fåtal innovationer för en slutgiltig diskussion med GIF angående finansiering. GIF räknar med att mindre än 5% av inkomna ansökningar lever upp till de hårda krav som krävs för finansiering. 

GIF accepterar tre olika sorters ansökningar beroende på ambitionsnivå och kapacitet hos innovatören - pilot, test and transition och scaling up. Tanken är att skräddarsy finansiering och eventuellt tekniskt stöd baserad på innovationens mognad. Vid varje stadie höjs ambitionsnivån och kraven på ansökan - en innovation kan gå genom alla steg men måste söka ny finansiering för varje steg i konkurrens med övriga sökanden. En central del i GIF är evidens och mätbara resultat. Tanken är att GIF ska möjlggöra för innovatörer att bevisa att deras innovation löser utvecklingsproblem på ett mer effektivt sätt än andra tillgängliga alternativ, och därmed få tillgång till ytterligare finansiering. 

GIF är ett icke vinstdrivande företag registrerat i Storbritannien. Företaget styrs av en VD som är ansvarig inför en styrelse, bestående av representanter från givare (Sida deltar som observatör) samt oberoende ledamöter, där de oberoende ledamöterna ska vara i majoritet. Styrelsen är i sin tur ansvarig gentemot GIF:s medlemmar, vilket i praktiken är samma sak som GIF:s givare eftersom alla som finansierar GIF har rätt att bli medlem. Det är viktigt att notera att medlemskap inte i någon mån innebär ägande - dvs Sida är inte en ägare av GIF och Sida bedömer därför att stödet inte strider mot Kapitalförsörjningslagen. 

GIF är ett givarinitierat program som är designat av främst USAID, DFID och Omidyar Network. Framförallt DIFD och USAID har varit mycket aktiva i designfasen, bl.a. genom att sekondera personal för att jobba med GIF under programmets uppbyggnadsfas. För att GIF ska fungera effektivt krävs att organisationen har stor flexibilitet och frihet att agera med liten hänsyn till strategiska prioriteringar och önskningar hos enskilda givare. Tanken är att givarna ska ha en begränsad roll i styrningen av GIF:s operativa arbete - istället ska den oberoend

title: UNESCO Enhancing Literacy in Afghanistan (ELA Phase III)
description:
UNESCO Programme for Enhancing of Literacy in Afghanistan (ELA) is a national programme that aims to improve the level of literacy numeracy and vocational skills of the adult population in all 34 provinces covering 750 000 learners. Afghanistan has one of 
the lowest literacy rates in the world currently estimated at over 30% of the adult population (over 15 years of age). Female literacy levels are on average 20 % while male literacy rate average is closer to 50 % both with high geographical variation. ELA 
will give priority to women aiming for at least 2/3 of total learners. Other priorities include rural areas Internally Displaced Persons Kuchi and other nomadic population and linguistic minorities. Finland's contribution of 2 million Euros will cover lite
racy training of 12 000 adults in four provinces: Farah Logar Panjsher and Parwan for 24 months in 2016-18. The total estimated cost for ELA programme is USD 37 million. Other ELA donors are Sweden and Japan.
Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland

title: New vaccine support (NVS) for ROTA
description: GAVIs support for new vaccines presents an opportunity for countries to not only implement vaccines that protect against diseases causing substantial morbidity and/or mortality, but also to build upon the vaccine investments in order to increase immunisation coverage rates, and strengthen routine immunisation services and primary health care systems. Rotavirus vaccine protects children against rotavirus disease and the severe and deadly diarrhoea that it causes in children. WHO recommends that rotavirus vaccination be included in all national immunization programmes, and the use of rotavirus vaccines should be part of a comprehensive strategy to control diarrhoeal diseases. Two oral rotavirus vaccines are currently available for routine infant immunisation with GAVI support: a two-dose schedule and the three-dose schedule vaccine.

title: The Western Region Rural Development Project
description:
PROJECT AREA/LOCATION:

The project has been conceived as a priority program to help develop the county's agricultural sector and particularly reduce poverty levels suffered by the poorest indigenous and non-indigenous groups in the Western Region of Guatemala.

PROJECT OBJECTIVES:

The project will comprise the following:
-  Creation of a Social Investment Fund
-  Establishment of a Productive Capitalization Fund
-  Implementation of institution strengthening and capacity building measures    across wide range of sectors
-  Provision of rural technical services and labor skills training. 

PROJECT COMPONENTS:

1.- Rural Development Participation and Decentralization
   A.- Decentralized management
   B.- Strengthening of local economic organizations
   C.- Consolidation of municipal decentralization process
   D.- Labor skill training
   E.- Social Investment Fund
2.- Marketing and Rural Business
   A.- Management of the component
   B.- Marketing technical assistance and training
   C.- Commercial development unit
   D.- Marketing and rural business infrastructure
3.- Rural Technical Services
   A.- Coordination of the component
   B.- Technical assistance services
   C.- Productive Capitalization Fund
   D.- Financial Service Access Fund
4.- Institutional Strengthening of the Executing Agency
5.- Decentralized Project Management Unit

title: Peace and Reconciliation Processes
description: Support and strengthen the negotiation process and implement peace and reconciliation processes, accords and ceasefire agreements at track levels 1, 2 and 3, including support to indigenous peacebuilding efforts. For a peace/negotiations process to have a chance of success, it must entail building trust in the process, between parties, and among their constituents, with a special focus on including women. Illustrative activities include negotiation training; platform development; public opinion polling; facilitation activities; elder statesmen engagement; provision of international expert advice and knowledge; financial support to parties; multi-stakeholder dialogues; assistance with the design of peacebuilding training programs; support and maintenance of agreed verification mechanisms; support to complaint tracking mechanisms; and work with local and national government representatives to bring them closer to their constituencies.

title: Accountability and safeguarding support for three partners working with indigenous communities
description: Through this project, CAFOD will support three strategic partners in Bolivia (Fundacion Nuna, CENDA and ACLO Potosi) in developing first drafts of child protection policies including codes of conduct, complaints handling mechanisms and policies covering communications and recruitment.  At the end of the training the participants will understand how to undertake their work without putting children at risk, how to recognise signs of abuse; how to manage child protection issues in a sensitive manner and how to manage a case of abuse, a complaint of abuse, suspicions or worries that abuse is occurring. Participants will have better understanding of CAFOD's requirements concerning child protection, CAFOD's own policy and standards and the support that partners can expect from CAFOD.  Participants will develop action plans for their institution during the training that set out steps to further develop their institutional policy and engage with communities and other actors.

description: (Zimbabwe):  USAID's Maternal and Child Health Integrated Program (MCHIP) provides technical assistance to the Ministy of Health and Child Care to improve the quality of maternal newborn and child health (MNCH) services delivered in Manicaland province. title: Rural Economic Development Initiative
description: The objective of the Rural Economic Development Initiative Project for Jamaica is to improve market access for micro and small-scale rural agricultural producers and tourism product and service providers. There are three components to the project. The first component of the project is rural subprojects in agriculture and rural tourism. This component will finance two types of rural subprojects: type A subprojects will support revenue generating activities in agriculture and tourism, and type B subprojects will support provision of critical infrastructure, marketing, and management in the agriculture and tourism sectors. The second component of the project is national technical assistance and capacity building. The main objective of this component is to strengthen relevant national organizations to enhance their capacity to continue assisting the rural enterprises and other project partners and ensure the sustainability of the rural enterprises. Hence, the component will finance technical assistance (TA) and capacity building for key organizations and agencies that deliver support services in agriculture and rural tourism at the local level. The third component of the project is project management. This component will finance project management, technical expertise (tourism and agricultural specialists, monitoring and evaluation) staff training, the annual audit, vehicles, office equipment, and other operating costs. This component will also ensure that effective fiduciary arrangements are in place during implementation.

title: Peru Cacao Alliance Phase II
description: (Peru):  Peru is the second largest cocaine producing country in the world. With U.S. support, the Government of Peru has adopted a successful counter-narcotics strategy focused on eradication, interdiction, and alternative development. Cacao is the most widely used crop substitute for coca in Peru. Under the first phase of the Peru Cacao Alliance, over 28,000 hectares of cacao were planted by more than 17,000 farmers. This activity, the second phase of the PCA (2016-2021), is implemented through a public-private partnership that includes 16 private enterprises, including cacao buyers, agricultural technology providers, lenders, and environmental investors. Together, these partners help improve farmer productivity and organization, and connect them to buyers in the growing global chocolate market, so they can earn a stable licit income and leave coca and poverty behind. FY 2018 funding will be used to scale up this public-private alliance's interventions to help at least 20,000 farmers improve cacao yields and quality. By the end of the five-year activity, USAID expects to leverage $50 million in private investment with a $25 million USAID investment, raise incomes for 20,000 households by an average of 30 percent, and increase cacao yields by 50 percent in areas formerly dominated by the production of coca used for cocaine. The alliance also helps formalize local businesses, boost trade, and support U.S. jobs. By increasing the supply of high quality cacao to U.S. markets, it feeds a flourishing confectionery industry that employs 70,000 U.S. workers along with a growing number of entrepreneurs and small businesses. The activity advances Embassy Lima's ICS Mission Objective 2.2 (to reduce the influence of transnational criminal organizations by sustaining coca reduction through alternative development) as well as NSS pillar II. The implementer was selected through a competitive process.

title: Emergency Humanitarian Assistance for the Democratic Republic of Congo - ICRC 2009
description: The situation remains extremely volatile in the eastern part of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), particularly in the provinces of North Kivu and Orientale. Renewed clashes between armed opposition groups with government forces and foreign troops are resulting in significant displacement, widespread looting, sexual and gender-based violence and a deterioration of humanitarian conditions. It is estimated that altogether over 1.4 million people remain displaced in DRC and that many have been displaced repeatedly. On a daily basis, displaced people face insecurity, weak health services, and lack of food, survival items, safe water and sanitation facilities.   CIDA's contribution is used to assist the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) in ensuring that displaced people and residents affected by armed conflict and violence have the means to survive and become self-sufficient. In addition, ICRC activities focus on ensuring that the wounded and sick receive adequate health care; helping to restore contact between separated family members; and reuniting displaced children with their families.
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) Appeals via the Canadian Red Cross Society (CRCS)

title: Simplified Clinical Tools and Educational Outreach for Health Workers
description: Developed in South Africa, simplified tools and training have been shown to improve outcomes for HIV, tuberculosis (TB) and primary care patients, and to enhance staff satisfaction and confidence. The following are key to their success: point-of-care training provided onsite in a clinical setting; case-based content; intermittent training sessions facilitated by peer trainers over time; and sustained educational support thereafter. This project will adapt the approach used in South Africa for Malawi, a more fragile health system where the challenge of integrating HIV services within primary care services is even greater. Working closely with the Ministry of Health and using a train-the-trainer model, researchers will test the approach, Simplified Tools and Training - Practical Approach to Lung Health, Malawi (STAT-PALM), in 31 rural health centres in Zomba district using a cluster-randomized trial. The training will focus on mid-level healthcare workers, that is, nurses, medical assistants and clinical officers. Outcomes measured will include staff retention and satisfaction, and patient outcomes with respect to HIV/AIDS, TB, malaria and other conditions seen in primary care. The overall goal is to improve access to high-quality HIV/AIDS care and primary care services.

title: F.a: Early Childhood Care and Development
description:
Project contributes to the holistic development of girls and boys under 8 years in safe and stimulating environments and strengthens the capacities of parents in supporting the development of their children. Foundations for a balanced growth and developmen
t of a child are laid in the early years of life, even pre-natal. Early childhood care and development (ECCD) and its importance for a child?s later development are not well known in Bolivia. The project supports the development of holistic, cross-sectoral
 ECCD services in 14 municipalities across Bolivia together with health-, education- and child protection authorities. Capacity-building is offered to parents on good parenting practices from a holistic perspective with a special focus on involvement of fa
thers in the care and development of their children. Educators and teachers are supported in providing quality, gender equal and stimulating care and education. In addition, work on advocacy is carried out in order to influence legislation and budgets rela
ted to ECCD. Target group of the project is 15000 children and 9000 parents as well as a number of different authorities. The project is implemented in co-operation with the participating municipalities.

title: Encourage Solarfonds
description: Das Vorhaben umfasst die Gründung und Ko-Finanzierung eines Fonds, der sich mit Eigenkapital an privaten Finanzinstitutionen beteiligen und mit diesen gemeinsam Kooperationen mit Solar-Projektentwicklern eingehen wird. In dieser Konstellation werden die Kooperationspartner Finanzierungslösungen und technisches Know-how für die Entwicklung des Solar-Dachanlagen-Marktes bereitstellen. Die Nutznießer der Solarfinanzierungen werden Kleinst-, kleine und mittlere Unternehmen (KKMU) sein, die bisher kaum an der Entwicklung des indischen Solarmarktes partizipiert haben. Unsere bisherigen Projekterfahrungen sowie die Gespräche mit Banken und Solarprojektentwicklern zeigen, dass insbesondere im Bereich der Solar-Finanzierungen für KKMU ein Engpass besteht. Die im Rahmen des Vorhabens unmittelbar unterstützten Gesellschaften (Finanzinstitute und Projektentwickler) sollen daher eine Vorreiter- und Demonstrationsfunktion für die Entwicklung dieses Marktes wahrnehmen. Damit leistet das Vorhaben einen wichtigen Beitrag zur Umsetzung der Deutsch-Indischen Solarpartnerschaft, insbesondere deren ersten Säule: Förderung von Photovoltaik (PV)-Dachanlagen.

title: Jobs Compact Ethiopia
description: The Ethiopian Jobs Compact will support the Government of Ethiopias industrialisation efforts, creating over 100,000 jobs for Ethiopians and refugees residing in the country. The Compact will match international support for job creation in Ethiopia to the gradual relaxation of the limitations on labour market access for 30,000 refugees. The job creation elements of the Compact would focus on Ethiopias ambitious industrialisation plans. This would support improvements in the investment climate, investment promotion, and improving environmental and social standards in the manufacturing sector. This would create over 100,000 jobs, mainly for young women, in global value chains such as garments and textiles. Support to refugees would include the necessary legislative changes but also training, relocation, rehousing and protection measures for this vulnerable group. It is anticipated that some of these employment opportunities for refugees would be in the manufacturing sector.

reporting.org: Swiss Agency for Development and Cooperation (SDC)
title: Economic prospects for young people in rural areas
description: The SDC project in rural Aswan Governorate in Egypt aims to improve the economic prospects of local young men and women. The SDC promotes enterprises in the agricultural, livestock breeding and fisheries sectors to create new jobs and provide young people with an alternative to migrating to urban centres.

In the Binga region of Zimbabwe, women face marginalization and exclusion, imbalances that are further exacerbated by recent political, food, fuel and financial crises. This programme seeks to contribute to rural women's economic empowerment in Binga by supporting their greater access to and utilization of natural resources in environmentally sustainable way, increasing their knowledge of biodiversity and sustainability and advocating for gender mainstreaming. The programme will reach out to women fishers, entrepreneurs, craft producers and fish traders in three wards, increasing their access to and capacity for sustainable fish farming (tilapia breams), kapenta fishing and exploitation of forest products such as baobab, jatropha, moringa and establishing ecotourism facilities. Moreover, the programme will support women's ability to develop better producer-market linkages and increase their knowledge of economic policies, resulting in higher incomes for rural women. As economically empowered women, they will then be better placed to tackle gender inequality issues in the public and private realms and resist abuse

title: CO-Mozambique Drought Emergency Recovery
description:
Oxfam:
Oxfam is a leading organization in emergency WaSH and Food Security in Mozambique since 1987.  Over the past five years Oxfam has implemented WaSH responses to benefit flood-affected populations in Sofala and Zambezia, cholera-affected populations in Sofala and Niassa, WaSH activities for east African refugees in Cabo Delgado and Nampula, and EFSL response for populations affected by three consecutive years of drought in Gaza.  In Mozambique Oxfam uses a single programmatic approach, linking activities in sustainable livelihoods, humanitarian assistance, good governance and gender for amore effective impact on beneficiaries.  In 2013, in coordination with COSACA members, Oxfam with its local partners implemented an emergency intervention to benefit more than 32,000 people in nine of the most flood-affected communities in Gaza and 8,000 people in Zambezia province through seeds and tools fairs, food security (EFSL) and access to safe water, sanitation and hygiene promotion (WASH).  The total funding mobilized was $2 million from theOxfam co-federation network and two bilateral donors.

Currently Oxfam is supporting 16,092 drought-affected households or 80,460individuals with FSL and WASH interventions and the food voucher system in Inhambane (Panda, Funhalouro, Mabote and Govuro districts), Sofala (Chemba District) and Maputo provinces (Matutuine, Moamba, Magude and Namaacha districts), together with its local partners. Oxfam proposes to cover the food insecure population in some IPC3/IPC4 districts. Those districts have been identified based on most recent figures and coordination with other agencies. The enrolment of additional districts will be considered if further funding becomes available in the coming months, which Oxfam continues to beactively seeking.

title: Valobservationer EU/OSSE 2015
description:
Valobservation syftar till att stärka demokrati i semi-auktoritära och repressiva stater med svaga demokratiska institutioner genom att bidra med internationella observatörer innan och under lokal-, parlaments- och presidentval, samt folkomröstningar. Internationella, oberoende valmissioner genom EU eller OSSE som verkar i ett land under en valprocess gång ger ökad transparens och synliggör brister i det demokratiska systemet. Genom att rapportera och följa upp efter ett val finns möjlighet att påverka nationella valmyndigheter och på så sätt uppnå en stärkt demokrati. Sedan 1989 har svenska valobservatörer deltagit i internationella valobservationsmissioner. Observatörerna rekryteras och utbildas av Sida på uppdrag av regeringen och ställs till EUs eller OSSEs förfogande.

Sida och Folke Bernadotte Academy (FBA) kommer under första kvartalet 2015 att ingå en tjänsteköpsöverenskommelse som innebär att FBA kommer att sköta viss hantering av valresursbasen, t ex utbildning (bl a förberedelse inför missioner och säkerhet), kommunikation och administration.

Insatsregelns förenklade hantering är bättre lämpad för beredning av valobservation med hänsyn till nedanstående synnerliga skäl:
1. Regeringsbeslut fattas för varje enskild valobservation i början av varje år.
2. Valobservatörer är arvodesanställda av Sida under uppdraget och Sida betalar arvode och utlandstillägg samt ersätter kostnader för resor och uppehälle mot reseräkning. Sida står också för kostnader för förberedelseutbildning. Risken för korruption eller att bidraget används felaktigt bedöms därför vara mycket liten. Endast en smärre administrativ avgift, oftast ej överstigande 10 tkr, rekvireras av OSSE efter varje valobservation.

reporting.org: Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland
title: Support for ostrich farm implementation
description:
After foreign fishing companies operating on the coast of Senegal have caused the local fishing business to disappear unemployment in Mlomp village is even higher than the average 48 % in Senegal. The nurishment has become less and is missing on protein. T
he planned ostrich farm will produce a remarkable change on this situation. The project will create employment in farming in processing meat and eggs in sales and logistics and processing skins into products. This is expected to bring work opportunities fo
r women and young unemployed in particular. Strong handicraft tradition prevails in the village. The main problem in the village is that practically no employment is available specially for young people. The ostrich farm would create jobs for approx. 10 pe
ople for growing fodder and animal care and a larger number of jobs in handicrafts. The Mlomp village lives in a large extent in barter economy growing rice and vegetables, the people have very little money. After the investment and revenues arriving from 
outside Mlomp many people would earn directly or indirectly some money either from working at the farm or from selling handicrafts or from selling vegetables for those who are employed. Even a small income may have the impact that people feel empowered to 
stay in the village instead of moving to the cities where no employment or food is easily available. The farm workers would have regular income and the candicraft producers income from sales. The major part of the revenue would flow for the Association to 
be used for mutual benefit like eg. the sick fund.
Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland

title: Filles Averties, Engagées, Hors de Danger
description: Au Tchad, les femmes et les filles subissent de lourdes injustices. Le rapport de lEnquête par grappes à indicateurs multiples (MICS 2010) a montré que 18% des femmes âgées de 15 à 49 ans ont été battues (violences physiques), 12% ont été victimes de violences sexuelles et 100% femmes ont été psychologiquement affectées. Dans beaucoup de communautés, les violences sexuelles sont acceptées et sont souvent moins rapportées par les femmes (Evaluation Final Programme UNFPA-Tchad 2012-2016, février 2016). Le pays est classé en 3ème position des pays enregistrant les taux de mariage denfants les plus élevés (67%) de lAfrique de lOuest et du Centre (Birdes not Girls, 2017). Les pratiques néfastes dont les Mutilations Génitales Féminines (MGF) et les mariages denfants persistent et les communautés ne font pas recours à des juridictions compétentes. Dans la sous-préfecture de Bouna, à linstar des autres localités du pays, ces pratiques se perpétuent. FAWE-Tchad propose de développer des actions de renforcement de capacité, dinformation et de sensibilisation des femmes et des communautés afin de protéger les droits des femmes.

title: Building Capacity of Phang Nga - Phuket Coastline Communities for Self-Reliance
description: This project will target communities along the Phang Nga  Phuket coastline, which have unique traditional cultures and ethnic identities that are closely linked to the sea. These communities depend directly on the natural resources of the coastline, which were devastated by the 2004 tsunami and are damaged further by commercial scale fishing, mining and over-exploitation of mangrove forests. This project will support 700 Muslim and Moken families in six communities in Phuket Province.  140 are original families and 560 are POG families. Project participants will undergo Values-Based Holistic Community Development (VBHCD) training and establish at least 28 self-help groups (SHGs).  Of all SHGs, 20 percent will be women-only. Heifer will provide 1,710 geese, 3,400 fingerling and 12,323.35 in funds for livelihood and income generating activities to eight original groups (4 SHGs will receive animals and 4 SHGs will receive funds). Also, animal feed fund worth 4132.18 will be made available to animal-raising SHGs.  Project participants will be trained on VBHCD, Cornerstones, Participatory Self Review and Planning (PSRP), group saving management, improved animal management, natural resource management, livelihood skills and co-learning. The original families will pass on all livestock, funds and knowledge. Moreover, this project hopes to empower SHGs to take the lead in participatory natural resource management, as well as establishing a network of government agencies and non-governmental organizations on sustainable community development and natural resource management.

title: "PROGRAMA PROPIO: PRACTICA Programa Meridies. ""Gestión de proyectos culturales para el desarrollo en el Centro Cultural de España en L
description: El Centro Cultural de España en La Paz, Bolivia (CCELP) pertenece a la Red de Centros Culturales de España en el exterior de la Agencia Española de Cooperación Internacional al Desarrollo. En un incio, el trabajo de la alumna giró en torno a su propia integración en el contexto del CCELP y de la ciudad de La Paz, de manera que su labor se centró en aquellos aspectos de urgencia en el centro así como en la escucha y la asimilación de los diferentes actores culturales que se relacionan asiduamente con el Centro. Tras unos meses de convivencia y diálogo en el CCELP, y una vez asimilado el contexto, se estableció un nuevo plan de trabajo útil a ambas instituciones: el CCELP y la consolidación de las materias aprendidas en el master de cooperacion al desarrollo de la UPV. Para ello se establecen tres puntos básicos: - Construir un diagnóstico propio, previo a la elaboración del Plan de Centro. - Consolidar las líneas estratégicas a partir del documento de la DRCC y de forma transversal en los proyectos y programas del centro. Especialmente, las de género y trabajo con las asociaciones locales. - Apoyar en la correcta elaboración del Plan de Centro.

title: Diakonia ram 2016-2020
description:
Programmet avser en femårsperiod (vilket beror på att ramorganisationerna i syfte att öka biståndseffektiviteten nu kan söka rambidrag för längre perioder än tidigare) och den baserar sig på Diakonias globala strategi för 2015-2020. Den omfattar 21 landprogram i Afrika, Asien, Latinamerika och Mellanöstern samt sex regionala program och ett globalt program för innovation inom området social och ekonomisk rättvisa. Diakonia arbetar genom lokala civilsamhällesorganisationer för det övergripande målet att förändra politiska, ekonomiska, sociala och kulturella strukturer som skapar fattigdom, förtryck och våld. Totalt 216 samarbetsparter ingår i ansökan. Verksamheten är inriktad på följande sex områden: mänskliga rättigheter (MR), demokrati, jämställdhet, social och ekonomisk rättvisa, konflikt och rättvisa, samt kapacitetsutveckling av samarbetsparter. Det som är nytt jämfört med tidigare är framför allt satsningen på fler regionala program inom olika områden samt det globala innovationsprogrammet.

Förväntade resultat:
Generella förväntade resultat formuleras för de sex områdena. Dessa är kopplade till förväntade resultat för varje program (dvs. per land/regionalt/globalt program), som i många fall består av ett urval resultat som är identiskt formulerade med de generella. Resultaten på programnivå konkretiseras genom indikatorer.

Exempel på förväntade resultat, ett från varje region, inom några vanliga tematiska områden är:
"Mali: Kvinnors politiska deltagande har stärkts på lokala och nationella nivåer" (demokrati)
"Bolivia: Genderbaserat våld har minskat" (jämställdhet)
"Bangladesh: Förutsättningarna för anständigt arbete och rättvis inkomst har förbättrats" (social och ekonomisk rättvisa)
"Libanon: Kapaciteten hos Diakonias samarbetsparter att integrera miljö och konfliktkänslighet i sitt arbete (där relevant) har förbättrats." (kapacitetsutveckling)

Tidigare resultat:
Resultatrapporteringen pekar ofta på resultat i termer av att rättighetsbärare har blivit stärkta och kapacitet hos samarbetsorganisationer har ökat. Exempel på tidigare resultat inom ett par områden:

MR: I Thailand har fem samarbetsorganisationer bistått tiotusentals statslösa personer i att uppnå juridisk status. Det innebär bl.a. att de fått rätt att arbeta och studera, samt tillgång till rättighetsbaserade tjänster.

Demokrati: I Mali har samarbetsorganisationer utbildats i medborgerlig budgetuppföljning och analys av offentlig politik. Det har lett till ökad budget för hälsa och utbildning i flera kommuner. I en provins publicerade alla kommuner sin ekonomiska redovisning 2014, till skillnad från 2012 då ingen kommun gjorde det.

Konflikt och rättvisa: Sju samarbetsorganisationer i Colombia, Honduras och Peru har ökat sin kunskap om det juridiska ramverket och har vidtagit legala åtgärder, som i några fall resulterat i att samhällen återvunnit mark från utvinningsföretag.

Grund för Sidas bedömning:
Samråd har inhämtats från ansvarig jurist vid Sidas avdelning för juridik och upphandling. Verksamhetscontrollern vid Sidas enhet för det civila samhället (CIVSAM) har konsulterats bl.a. för budgetfrågor. Synpunkter har också begärts in från de svenska utlandsmyndigheter (UM) samt andra enheter på Sida som hanterar bilaterala avtal med Diakonia. Därutöver har granskningar gjorts av integreringen av tvärfrågor i Diakonias verksamhet genom Sidas ramavtal för jämställdhet, helpdesk för miljö och klimat, respektive mänsklig säkerhet. 

Sidas bedömning av Diakonias ansökan baseras huvudsakligen på följande dokument:
- Slutrapport från ramkriteriebedömningen av Diakonia 2013 (Doxnr. 027413/13)
- Diakonias slutrapportering till CIVSAM för rambidraget 2012-2014 (Doxnr. 016518/15, 035857/15)
- Underlag från 12 UM samt två enheter vid Sida (för Doxnr. se avsnitt 7a i berednings-PM).
- Dokument relaterade till revisionsprocessen av Diakonia för 2012 och 2013 (Doxnr. 016523/13, 019056/14, 019049/14, 034408/14) 
- Stickprovsrevision av Diak

title: Vers plus d'autonomisation
description:
L'objectif général s'éclatent en trois objectifs spécifiques, à savoir:
Objectif Spécifique 1: Accompagner les groupes PIEPP et les GVF dans le renforcement des capacités et le développement des activités économiques.
Objectif Spécifique 2: Consolider les liens entre les acteurs des 9 Pôles dEntreprises Agricoles où les organisations de producteurs de la FEPA.B sont les portes dentrées.
Objectif Spécifique 3: Renforcer les capacités organisationnelles et de gestion de 07 UPPA de la FEPA.B disposant de plans dactions pilotes.

Cela devra aboutir aux résultats suivants: 
Résultat 1 : la situation économique des groupes locaux PIEPP et GVF de microcrédit a évolué.  
Résultat 2 : Les liens entre les acteurs des 9 PEA où les OP de la FEPA.B constituent les portes dentrées sont consolidés ; 
Résultat 3 : Linnovation au  niveau organisationnel et managérial des unions sest accrue
Résultat 4 : Le suivi des activités réalisées par la coordination les unions et les groupes locaux est effectif
Résultat 5 : Les  organes de la  FEPA.B et la coordination technique fonctionnent de façon efficiente

Ainsi les activités suivantes sont prévues: 
	Formation en planification participative et suivi des activités
Les 07 unions à plans pilotes ciblées seront accompagnées dans la planification et le suivi annuel de leurs activités. Des sessions de planification permettront aux unions disposant de plans provinciaux (07) de lactualiser (pour prendre en compte le niveau local avec les groupes PIEPP, les GVF et les PEA au niveau de chaque province), de le mettre en uvre et de le suivre. Ces 7 unions seront accompagnées dans lexécution dau moins 60% de leurs activités planifiées.
 
	Poursuite de la structuration des OP à la base
Les orientations de la Stratégie de Développement Rural (SDR) à lhorizon 2015, retiennent lapproche filière comme démarche pour accroître, diversifier et intensifier les productions agro-sylvo-pastorales en liaison avec les besoins du marché. En effet, la démarche filière vise la conquête des marchés à travers lamélioration des circuits dapprovisionnement identifiés. 

	Formation à lauto-évaluation des activités
Lauto-évaluation des activités est un exercice qui permet de se retourner pour voir le chemin parcouru et corriger les erreurs pour atteindre lobjectif visé. Les unions cibles et les animateurs seront formés en auto-évaluation participatives des activités. Ce qui les permettrait dapprendre de leurs erreurs. Des sessions dauto-évaluations appuyées par la coordination technique  seront organisées au sein de ces unions. 

* Les activités de renforcement des capacités économiques 
La visibilité de la FEPA-B se traduit par sa capacité de mobilisation de ses ressources internes. Au cours de lannée 2011, les sensibilisations à la participation financière des activités vont se poursuivre avec les sorties dappui conseil. Il faut quà terme, les membres comprennent quune fédération qui se veut crédible comme la FEPA.B doit montrer à ses partenaires quelle est capable de mobiliser dimportantes ressources propres. Lobjectif pour 2011 est que 80% des membres soient à jour de leurs cotisations.

	Suivi des activités à tous les niveaux : local, UPPA et central

	Renforcement de la mobilisation des ressources externes 
Il est clair que dans la vision de la FEPA.B, la mobilisation des ressources financières propres est la première priorité pour mettre en uvre les actions au profit des membres. Toutefois, au regard des ambitions qui ne cessent daccroitre, il devient de plus en plus difficile de ne pas solliciter laccompagnement extérieur. 

	Ateliers  d'élaboration  de projets
Dans loptique de participer aux appels à candidatures de lUnion Européenne et à tout autre appel qui serait lancé, la FEPA.B prévoit 3 ateliers en vue délaborer les projets à soumettre pour financement.
  
	Elaboration dun plan daction triennal 2012-2014 
Le plan daction 2008-2011 arrive à terme en décembre 2011. Il sera nécessaire de disposer dun document prêt en novembre 2011 pour soumettre aux partenaires. Ce document prendra en compte les insuffisances constatées dans la mise en uvre du plan 2008-2011 et aura un souci de faire participer une fois de plus lensemble des acteurs qui sont aussi bénéficiaires des actions. 

	Tenue des rencontres régulières de la coordination
La coordination poursuivra  la  tenue régulière des rencontres toutes les 2 semaines pour partager les informations et planifier les sorties terrain. Au total, 20 rencontres seront tenues au cours de lannée.

La proposition de projet poursuit avec les activités deja en cours. Il s'agit notamment des groupes locaux PIEPP (promotion des initiatives économiques par la participation paysanne) et les groupements de femmes qui bénéficient des micro-crédit. Aussi les PEA créés au sein de la FEPA-B bénéficieront de l'appui.

L'objectif général est d'accompagner ces groupes locaux, membres de la FEPA-B en vue d'accroitre leurs capacités de production, de commercilaisation et de transformation des produits agricoles.

title: Avian Influenza Risk : Characterization and Dynamics of Backyard Poultry Raising Systems in Five Asian Countries
description: The highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) virus H5N1 produces severe disease and high mortality in domestic poultry, waterfowl and other bird species. Public health authorities are concerned that this strain may mutate to became contagious between people. Throughout Southeast Asia and China, farmers raise poultry in small backyard flocks that scavenge around the farms and in the case of ducks in paddy fields. Ducks can carry the virus without showing clinical symptoms and it is suspected that some wild species may also form a reservoir of H5N1. The backyard poultry sector, where different species mix freely and come into direct contact with humans, therefore poses a particular risk. Governments in the region have adopted or are considering policies that call for restructuring or even eliminating the smallholder poultry sector, which could have a considerable impact on the livelihoods of poor farmers. This grant will allow researchers in Cambodia, China, Indonesia, Thailand and Viet Nam to examine the backyard poultry sector in their respective countries and its role in rural livelihoods. The researchers will work with stakeholders to devise practical, equitable and sustainable options for reducing the likelihood of a human avian influenza pandemic.

title: Emergency Regional Funding for Africa and the Middle East - ICRC Appeals 2016
description: The International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) primary mission is to help protect the lives and dignity of people affected by conflict and other situations of violence. The ICRC provides assistance and prevents further suffering by promoting and strengthening international humanitarian law and universal humanitarian principles.  With the support of GAC and other donors, the ICRCs emergency operations aim to provide protection, food assistance, health services, livelihood support and other essential services to populations affected by armed conflict and other situations of violence, as well as to promote respect for international humanitarian law. This funding supports appeals for countries in North Africa, Western Africa and the Middle East. Project activities include: (1) protecting and assisting those who are vulnerable to abuse during hostilities by providing comprehensive hospital care and access to water and restoration of livelihoods; (2) providing Red Cross/Red Crescent National Societies with technical expertise in areas such as promotion of international humanitarian law, restoring family links and health care provision in situations of armed conflict and violence; and (3) ensuring that international humanitarian law is respected in the treatment of civilians not taking part in hostilities, as well as for detainees.

title: Diversification of Seaweed Industries
description: Seaweed is an important commodity for aquaculture in the Pacific. Its farming is culturally and technologically appropriate, able to provide substantial livelihood benefits to men and women in remote communities, and is potentially export-oriented. There is renewed commercial interest in seaweed, with an identified need for diverse products in addition to the commonly produced carrageenan (used as a food thickener and stabiliser). This project will investigate methods to improve production of both carrageenan-producing seaweeds and edible seaweeds in Fiji, Samoa and Kiribati for local and export markets. It will also assess opportunities for new seaweed products, such as fertilisers, stock feeds and biologically active chemicals.

title: Strengthening Adaptation and Resilience to Climate Change in Kenya Plus (StARCK+)
description: To achieve transformational change by helping Kenya to scale up private sector innovation and investment in low carbon and adaptation products, services and assets (e.g. clean energy, sustainable agriculture, water management, weather forecasting). Enabling this change will require targeted support to critical aspects of climate change governance, and stimulation of civil society demand. This contributes to the UK Governments International Climate Fund (ICF) commitments and will benefit 828,000 people able to cope with the effects of climate change and 17,600 people with improved access to clean energy.

title: Australia Awards - 2014 intake
description: The Australia Awards are international scholarships and fellowships funded by the Australian Government offering the next generation of global leaders an opportunity to undertake study, research and professional development. The Awards strive to develop leadership potential and stimulate lasting change by empowering a global network of talented individuals through high-quality education experiences in Australia and overseas. Recipients return home with new ideas and knowledge, and the ability to make a significant contribution to their home countries as leaders in their field. Funding under this initiative supports the global delivery for the 2014 Intake and is valued at $393.2 million over 8 years, starting 2013-14.
